<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): US markets move back to
record levels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
The US stock market bounced back from three losing sessions yesterday as
share prices, buoyed by heavy programme trading, moved back into record
territory, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 24.77 at 3,867.20,
past its previous record close of 3,865.51, set on Monday. The more broadly
based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 also ended firmer, up 2.40 at 474.87, while the
Amex composite finished up 0.82 at 480.88, and the Nasdaq composite 4.49
closed higher at 792.31, also a new record high. Trading volume on the NYSE
was 305m shares, and rises outpaced declines by 1,238 to 857.
Three days of modest declines on profit-taking have done nothing to dampen
investors' enthusiasm for equities. The market bounced back strongly
yesterday from the losses of earlier in the week, and within 90 minutes of
the opening the Dow was back above Monday's record close.
Market sentiment was aided by good economic news in the form of a 0.7 per
cent increase in December industrial output, which was bigger than analysts
had expected. The production figures, coming on the heels of good news on
inflation and retail sales, bolstered optimism about the outlook for the
economy in 1994, and prompted fresh buying of equities.
Banks remained in demand in anticipation of a strong fourth quarter from the
industry. Citicorp rose another Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 42 1/8 , JP Morgan
climbed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 71 1/2 , BankAmerica firmed Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 48 7/8 and Chase Manhattan put on Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 35 7/8 .
Kaufman &amp; Broad fell Dollars 3 to Dollars 21 1/2 in early trading after the
home construction company reported disappointing fourth-quarter earnings.
The stock later recovered, however, and it finished down only Dollars  7/8
at Dollars 23 5/8 .
Among Dow stocks that were higher in the wake of buy pro grammes were Walt
Disney, up Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 47 5/8 , General Electric, up Dollars 1
5/8 at Dollars 106 7/8 and American Express, up Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 32.
On the Nasdaq market, Ask Group fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 10 1/8 after the
computer company announced job cuts and reported a fiscal second-quarter
loss.
Canada
Toronto stocks posted a small gain in active trading yesterday to close at
another record high. The TSE composite index added 9.24 points, or 0.21 per
cent, to 4,489.14. Volume was 86.7m shares compared with Thursday's 84.7m.
</TEXT>
