<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Power stocks weak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLARE GASCOIGNE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Power generation stocks were among the market's worst performers with
utilities specialists saying that all the utilities sectors, which attract
support because of their high yields and quality of earnings, may suffer in
the absence of any UK interest rate reductions in the short term.
The generators were the worst affected, with UBS, the Swiss-owned
stockbroking firm, said to have been an aggressive seller. There were also
suggestions that PowerGen and National Power could be about to sell some
power stations, to try to head off a referal to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Just before Christmas, Offer, the electricity watchdog, said the English
generators could avoid an MMC referral if they came up with an acceptable
pricing regime and sold some of their power stations.
The Scottish generators were heavily sold, Scottish Power sliding 13, or 2.9
per cent, to 441p, on heavy turnover of 5.2m shares. Hydro dipped 11, or 2.5
per cent to 436p. National Power fell 11, or 2.3 per cent, to 467p and
PowerGen 9 to 535p.
</TEXT>
