<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A squeeze as UK institutions turned aggressive buyers of the London market
sent futures contracts sharply forward and brought heavy dealing in the
traded options, writes Joel Kibazo.
After an erratic week of exaggerated swings, buyers were seen for the March
futures contract on the FT-SE 100 from the outset as it opened at 3,382.
Dealers said US houses that had been prominent sellers in the last two
sessions had remained on the sidelines as UK institutions moved in.
March lost some momentum mid-session, as traders used the earlier advance to
arbitrage between the cash and the futures markets. However, a good premium
to cash was maintained throughout the day. It closed at 3,425, just ahead of
its fair value premium to cash of 13 points, on volume of 16,688 lots.
Turnover in the traded options jumped to a hefty 56,696 lots with heavy
trading in the FT-SE 100 option bring closing volume of 22,493.
</TEXT>
