<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Investors to vote on Beverley debt
proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER and MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders in Beverley Group, the engineering concern previously known as
Petrocon, will decide on Monday whether to sell a number of businesses and
properties to a vehicle controlled by its directors in a series of complex
deals which the company said was designed to reduce debt.
Investors will also be asked to approve the sale of Gall Thomson Marine,
Beverley's most profitable subsidiary, to Villiers, the USM-quoted
engineering company, for up to Pounds 4m.
In a prospectus sent to shareholders, dated December 31, Beverley proposes
to sell two wholly owned subsidiaries, Beverley Group (Almondsbury) Ltd
(BGAL) and ESL, for Pounds 1 each to Woodlands Grange Engineering, the
executive directors' privately owned company.
Beverley's three independent directors, advised by stockbroker Henry Cooke
Corporate Finance, recommend the transactions to shareholders as 'vital to
the group's future'.
However, some shareholders are believed to be unhappy with the property and
business disposals to Woodland Grange.
For example, the agreement leaves one of the subsidiaries being sold, BGAL,
with Pounds 237,000 in cash. The directors say this is equivalent to the
amount which Beverley would have paid in redundancies if it closed the
business. However, these employees will not be made redundant when ownership
is transferred.
The transactions also include the sale of ESL, a surveying subsidiary.
Beverley is writing off inter-company debt of Pounds 821,000 and repaying a
Pounds 359,000 bank overdraft. The circular says fully audited accounts for
all the businesses in ESL are not available after 1991.
Once they are part of Woodlands Grange, BGAL's employees will still be able
to provide management and administrative services to Beverley Group. Mr
Colin Robinson, chairman, said this allowed Beverley to retain access to its
acquisition team, when the time was ripe for expansion. Under the agreement,
fees for such services cannot exceed Pounds 70,000 this year, unless one
non-executive director approves an increase. Mr Robinson said Beverley had
decided not to close ESL because this would have entailed significant costs
for the company.
Woodlands Grange is also buying three properties from Beverley for a total
of Pounds 997,000, some Pounds 650,000 less than book value.
Shareholder concern is focused on the valuations of the properties,
including the head office at Woodlands Grange, Bristol, which is being sold
to the directors' private company for Pounds 612,000. The property is held
in Beverley's books at Pounds 1.1m.
Beverley will continue to occupy at least 50 per cent of the property for an
annual rent payable to Woodlands Grange Engineering of Pounds 51,000. The
circular says the lease contains an option allowing Beverley to occupy
further space in the building.
Another property, in Great Yarmouth, is being sold to Woodland Grange for
Pounds 185,000. This property yields net income of Pounds 48,000 a year.
Mr Robinson said that 'in order for the group to have adequate working
capital for its present requirements, it is necessary that the disposals are
approved by shareholders'.
Mr Robinson, who has previously worked for Gerald Ronson's Heron and Robert
Maxwell at Hollis Industries, took a stake in Petrocon in 1991 intending to
expand the group through acquisition.
The first purchase was Beverley, the vehicle for the private interests of Mr
Robinson, his wife, Eleanor, Mr Christopher Colbeck and Mr Michael Bridge.
Petrocon then changed its name to Beverley. Mr Colbeck, Mrs Robinson and Mr
Bridge are now directors of the quoted company.
Mr Robinson said recession and the discovery of 'significant problems' in
Petrocon had forced the board to abandon its expansion strategy.
The group also incurred substantial costs last year in its abortive and
highly controversial Pounds 35m bid for James Wilkes, the rival engineering
company.
</TEXT>
<XX>
