<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / Anger over 'the all-round con'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Warwick and Brindley estate is sandwiched between the Westway motorway
and the Harrow Road in a poor backwater of Westminster.
Some of its residents provide graphic accounts to illustrate the council's
determination to sell off its housing during the 1980s. Tenants in the six
tower blocks who yielded to council pressure to buy their properties
bitterly regret their decisions.
They say any savings from ownership are cancelled out by service and other
charges which they pay and tenants do not. More importantly, because only a
few properties were sold-off, there is no market and they cannot sell their
flats.
Only 85 of the 600 flats were sold before the designated sales policy came
to an end in that estate in 1988.
Since then the council has been moving in homeless families from
bed-and-breakfast accommodation and others who cannot afford to pay rent.
Mrs Winifred Donald, a retired London Transport worker, says: 'In the
mid-1980s whenever a property became vacant, they put a steel door on to
prevent squatters. The council told us the properties would be sold.
'We have lived here since the beginning 30 years ago. We bought in 1987
because it was so cheap. We paid Pounds 17,000 which was about 30 per cent
of its value, although there was an indemnity which we paid off over five
years.
'But now they have moved all these income-support people in. I've nothing
against them, mind, but we will never sell the place now. I voted
Conservative last time - I am certainly not going to vote Conservative next
time.'
Mrs Donald wanted to sell the property for Pounds 50,000 and move near to
her son in Reading. She says: 'We have had no interest, and they've loaded
charges on to us. We have been conned.'
Mr Robert Fox, 72 , a retired brewery worker has also been soured by the
experience.
'They (the council) kept punching away at us to buy. They said it would be
cheaper than renting and that they wanted to sell the whole block,' he says.
'We bought because I've got two boys and I thought it would give them a bit
of security. I bought it for Pounds 15,000 with a Pounds 10,000 indemnity.
Even with the indemnity this was only 40 per cent of its face value. I
bought it out of savings.
'But now they are putting all these charges on us. We have to pay Pounds
4.50 for gates and a concierge they want to put in. They want thousands from
us for repairs to the outside of the building. They are not asking the
tenants, most of them can't pay anyway.
'I could not sell the place even if I wanted to although it is supposed to
be worth Pounds 60,000. If anything happened to me or my wife my sons could
not pay the charges and the place would be repossessed. It's been one
all-round con.'
</TEXT>
