FT  15 JAN 94 / Venezuela tries to save Banco Latino
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Venezuelan president, Mr Ramon Velasquez, was meeting yesterday with the
country's monetary authorities in an effort to save Banco Latino, the
country's second largest commercial bank, which closed its doors after
suffering serious financial problems.
National Guardsmen were posted outside Banco Latino's headquarters in
Caracas yesterday and the bank, with branches nationwide, was closed. There
was no indication when it might re-open.
The government is viewed by financial experts as trying to avoid direct
intervention, which could prove expensive, and has urged other banks to
provide assistance to Banco Latino.
Its board said it had suffered 'a criminal rumour campaign' over the past
three months that caused the loss of over Dollars 500m in deposits.
The Venezuelan banking system was calm yesterday but prices of Venezuelan
government bonds in the international markets fell as much as 4 per cent
before recovering slightly.
The Minister of Finance, Mr Carlos Rafael Silva, said that the authorities
had to determine whether Banco Latino's problem was 'illiquidity or
insolvency'.
Banco Latino, which over the past year offered among the country's highest
interest rates on deposits, began suffering from a severe liquidity crunch
last month, and received large sums in rediscounts and advances from the
Central Bank. Despite this, on Thursday, the bank could not meet its
obligations in the national cheque clearing system.
