<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / Portillo blunts PM's drive for unity on 'back to basics'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's attempts to end the controversy over Mr John Major's 'back
to basics' programme ran into fresh difficulties last night.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, led a concerted cabinet campaign to
restore intellectual coherence to the call for a return to traditional
values.
But his emphasis on a common sense approach across the range of government
policies was followed by a sharp attack from Mr Michael Portillo, the chief
secretary to the Treasury, on critics of Britain's national traditions and
institutions.
Despite clearance for his speech from Downing Street, Mr Portillo, a leading
cabinet right winger, faced charges from some on the Tory left that he was
flouting Mr Major's authority.
But the prime minister's office rejected as 'malicious fiction' reports last
night that Mr Major had launched an outspoken attack on right-wing members
of the cabinet during private conversations which took place earlier this
week.
Referring to a 'new British disease', Mr Portillo castigated critics of the
monarchy, parliament and the established church. He blamed what he called
the anti-establishment chattering classes for spreading the 'poison of
pessimism' which undermined national self-confidence and respect for British
institutions.
Mr Portillo told an audience of the rightwing Conservative Way Forward Group
that our 'our mission must be to rebuild national self-confidence and
self-belief'. He said: 'We need to assert the value and the quality of the
British way of life and of British institutions.'
Mr Hurd sought to disentangle the central message of 'back to basics' from
the private lives of ministers and Conservative MPs, by insisting that it
represented a 'commonsense' approach to the much wider concerns of the
electorate.
His emphasis on the government's drive to improve standards in schools, to
nurture the economic recovery and to redouble the fight against crime was
echoed in speeches and interviews by several other cabinet ministers.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, also joined Mr Hurd in urging the government's
supporters to 'keep their nerve' during the present storm.
Setting out the line agreed by the cabinet in an effort to rescue the 'back
to basics' programme, the foreign secretary said politicians should not set
themselves up as the arbiters of personal morality.
Nor should the personal failings of some politicians be mistaken for the
fortunes of the government, said Mr Hurd.
Mr Hurd's confident exposition, however, did little to disguise the debate
still raging in the cabinet and in the Conservative party concerning the
extent to which the government should set a moral tone for the nation.
Mr John Redwood, the Welsh secretary, and Mr John Patten, the education
secretary, are among those in the cabinet who believe a programme promoting
the difference between right and wrong cannot avoid touching on individual
morality.
