<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / MMC to investigate video games makers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is to investigate whether video games
manufacturers, notably Sega and Nintendo of Japan, are over-charging
consumers and unfairly restricting competition.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director general of Fair Trading, said yesterday that he
had ordered the probe after an increasing number of consumers had complained
that prices of new games were higher in Britain than in the US.
Retailers had complained about manufacturers' distribution practices, while
software publishers were frustrated by the licensing arrangements for
production of games used on the leading brands of hardware.
The move was welcomed by the Consumers Association, which has repeatedly
criticised manufacturers' prices and marketing practices. Sega and Nintendo
said they would co-operate with the MMC but insisted the market was fully
competitive.
The two companies account for about 90 per cent of the British video games
market, worth more than Pounds 700m last year, three times more than in
1991. Games hardware costs between Pounds 50 and Pounds 300, while games
prices range from Pounds 10 to Pounds 60 for new releases.
Sega said it was surprised by the inquiry, and Nintendo said the UK video
games market was the most competitive in the world. Conditions were
particularly fierce at Christmas, when about 40 per cent of all toys sold
were video games.
There have recently been signs that some prices are softening. Dixons, the
electrical retailer, said last week that it expected lower profits this
year, partly because of a price war in video game consoles launched by the
Woolworths and Comet chains.
However, some independent surveys late last year found that retail prices of
new games were as much as 50 per cent higher in Britain than in the US.
The MMC, which is due to report by the end of October, is expected to focus
on complaints by retailers and independent software publishers, which
produce about half the games sold by Nintendo and Sega.
Some retailers have told the Office of Fair Trading that they have been
compelled to buy exclusively from the two companies and prevented from
obtaining the same items more cheaply from other sources abroad.
Some small retailers, particularly rental outlets, have also claimed that
they are supplied with new games only after they are on sale in bigger
chains.
Independent software publishers have complained that Sega and Nintendo use
licensing arrangements and their policies of manufacturing all the games
used on their machines to restrict the supply of new products to the market.
