<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / Sharp increase in US output lifts shares to new highs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US industrial production grew at an annual rate of 7.5 per cent in real
terms in the fourth quarter of last year, a further sign of the accelerating
pace of economic recovery, figures from the Federal Reserve indicated
yesterday.
The news prompted a strong rise in share prices, which reached record highs
in early trading. By midday the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 30.40 at
3,872.83. Bond prices fell on fears that faster growth would bring forward
the timing of an interest rate rise.
As the Clinton administration puts the final touches to this year's budget,
due early next month, senior officials are increasingly confident about the
economic outlook.
In an upbeat address in New York yesterday, Mr Robert Rubin, chairman of the
White House National Economic Council, forecast a robust, sustained
recovery. He said there was 'very little probability of inflation
reigniting' and predicted 3 per cent growth this year.
Mr Rubin said economic conditions would also be favourable in 1995 and 1996
because, by then, the US would be getting a boost from economic recovery in
Japan and Europe.
In an apparent preview of the budget, Mr Rubin also predicted that the US
would make more rapid progress than expected in reducing the federal budget
deficit.
The deficit would fall to 'substantially under 2 per cent of GDP' over five
years, he said. Last year's budget projected a deficit of 3.1 per cent of
GDP in 1998.
The Fed report showed production up 0.7 per cent in December after strong
gains in preceding months. Although led by a surge in car production, output
strength appears broadly based. Nearly every industrial sector registered
gains. Excluding cars, production was up 0.5 per cent last month, the same
rise as in November.
The rate of industrial capacity utilisation rose to 83.5 per cent, above its
long-term average of 81.9 per cent but still below the 84.8 registered at
the peak of the 1980s boom.
Preliminary figures suggest that the first quarter got off to a good start.
The University of Michigan's closely-watched consumer sentiment index was
reported to have risen sharply in early January to 95.8 against 88.2 in
December.
The rise is a reassuring sign that consumers are not reducing their spending
after the Christmas period.
Separate data released yesterday showed business inventories up 0.6 per cent
in November. However, they failed to keep pace with the growth in business
sales, which rose by 1.1 per cent.
As a result, the inventory-to-sales ratio slipped to 1.44, its lowest level
since 1982, raising the prospect of increased production if consumer demand
continues to rise this year.
Currencies, Page 11
US stocks, Page 19
Markets, Weekend II
