<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 94 / Porter attacks district auditor's findings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dame Shirley Porter, at the centre of this week's row over allegations of
gerrymandering at Westminster city council, last night attacked the judgment
of the Westminster district auditor and vowed to fight her case to the House
of Lords in a bid to clear her name.
Speaking to the Financial Times from Palm Springs, California, where she is
on holiday, Dame Shirley dismissed as 'ludicrous' the suggestion that Pounds
21.25m had been wasted as a result of Conservative-controlled Westminster's
council house sales policy.
Dame Shirley, leader of Westminster council until 1991, said she refuted
'everything' in this week's damning report by Mr John Magill, the district
auditor, who said in provisional findings that Dame Shirley and nine other
people connected with the council might have to repay the money alleged to
have been wasted.
During a 20-minute telephone conversation, Dame Shirley, in confident mood,
said she rejected the methodology on which Mr Magill's report had been
based. She had lined up a 'leading firm' of accountants - which she was not
prepared to name - to counter the suggestions made in the findings from Mr
Magill, who is a leading accountant at Touche Ross.
Asked about suggestions that she had disposed of documents pertinent to the
inquiry, Dame Shirley said: 'I have not disposed of anything at any time.'
She accused Mr Magill of 'making a new law' in his provisional findings.
These were seized upon this week by Labour politicians who claimed they
demonstrated the weakened moral authority of the Conservative government.
Dame Shirley said she had 'complete faith' in the judgment of Mr Jeremy
Sullivan, Queen's Counsel who acts for Westminster council and who had
assured her and other council officers that the authority's housing policies
were legal.
Tories divided over the Westminster effect, Page 4
