<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / (CORRECTED) Technology: Japanese elevator girls bow out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 21st January 1994) appended to this article.
For many Japanese, one of the pleasures of shopping in up-market department
stores has been riding the lifts, operated by 'elevator girls' - smartly
dressed in designer uniforms, bowing and smiling while pressing the buttons
to each floor.
Selecting the floors of the automated lifts has long been considered an
important 'service' by both retailer and customer. But due to the consumer
slump and new technology, Japanese shoppers may soon find themselves
pressing their own lift buttons and being greeted instead by a computerised
screen.
Many department store operators are now being forced to restructure their
operations because of the sharp fall in retail spending, especially on
luxury items. The economic downturn has brought about a radical change in
consumer spending patterns, and even the most prestigious operators are
falling into the red.
Fujitec, a leading elevator maker, claims to have the answer for the
department store operators caught between the need to cut costs and
customers who still consider a smile and a warm welcome as an important
attraction.
The company has developed jointly with Sanyo Electric a computerised
information system for department store lifts where a female attendant on
screen smiles and bows, reciting wares to customers. A system for four
elevators costs around Y10m (Pounds 595,200), which Fujitec claims is
cheaper than hiring four elevator girls.
A customer entering the lift will be greeted by a female attendant on a
screen display above the lift door. While the lift is moving, the screen
will display product and shopping information, and when the lift stops,
floor information will flash on to the screen followed by a bowing
attendant.
Fujitec says it has received inquiries from several department stores. The
company says the system can also be used for screening advertisements or
scenery in lifts in ordinary office buildings, providing something for
people to look at.
CORRECTION
In the article on January 14 headed 'Japanese elevator girls bow out', the
sterling equivalent of the Y10m cost of the lift information system was
given wrongly as Pounds 595,200 instead of Pounds 59,520.
</TEXT>
