<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Markets in Asia fall as investors take profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL MORGAN and JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Asia's equity markets suffered a sharp decline in trading yesterday, led by
a 5.9 per cent plunge in Taiwan and a 5 per cent tumble in Hong Kong.
Analysts said the turnround after the recent phenomenal rise in the region
was due to selling by US and Japanese retail investors, with institutional
funds remaining committed.
They also pointed out that while the decline was broadly based, there was no
common theme behind yesterday's falls as markets reacted to domestic news
and developments.
Taiwan's slide, for instance, was largely the result of dashed hopes of
stronger links with mainland China.
Hong Kong's fall marked a third consecutive day of selling. In subsequent
London trading of Hong Kong shares, buyers returned, taking the indicative
market index up by 2 per cent, and some brokers expect the market to bounce
back today.
Kuala Lumpur and Bangkok saw 3 per cent falls, while Singapore and Manila
were both down by more than 2 per cent.
Many of south-east Asia's markets surged last year, with much of the rise in
the final quarter after US and Japanese banks and brokers, notably Morgan
Stanley and Nomura, put out strong recommendations. Manila rose by almost
155 per cent, Hong Kong by over 115 per cent and Kuala Lumpur by 98 per
cent.
Analysts say this left the region vulnerable to investors who wanted to cash
in profits, which was confirmed last week when some previously bullish
strategists downgraded their views on the region's attractions. The result
has been a cumulative 19.3 per cent slide in Kuala Lumpur since the start of
this year, and falls of over 14 per cent in Hong Kong and Bangkok.
World markets and currencies, Section II
