<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: TSB strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The banks sector was electrified by much better than expected preliminary
figures from TSB, the first of the UK high street banks to report this year.
TSB shares, which have consistently underperformed the sector and the
market, surged ahead as the profits and dividend news hit the market, ending
15 stronger at 267p, after touching a record 273p.
Turnover of 47m shares almost matched the stock's debut in October 1986 when
50m changed hands. The activity was boosted by a placing of 9.3m shares at
264p, said to have been executed by NatWest Securities. Blocks of TSB shares
were placed at 266p as the market closed.
Dealers said the driving force behind the share price was the 20 per cent
dividend increase, which outstripped the market's best expectations of
around 9.5 per cent. Analysts said the market was now expecting dividend
rises of 10 per cent in subsequent years. Current year forecasts were
hoisted to between Pounds 440m and Pounds 450m, and for 1995 to around
Pounds 550m.
The TSB figures were seen as indicating a sector-wide rerating of banks,
with Abbey National the main beneficiary. Abbey shares leapt to 510p before
closing 21 ahead at 507p on turnover of 11m.
A banks analyst said: 'Abbey responded to good news from its Scottish Mutual
business, the widespread feeling that the recession is over and perceptions
that it is more geared to the recovering housing/mortgage market.' He added
that the market had upgraded its dividend expectations for Abbey following
the TSB figures.
