<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Nervous pressure on oils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading oil issues came under growing selling pressure as institutions
fretted about persistent weakness in crude oil prices and the forthcoming
privatisation of Elf Aquitaine, the French state-owned oil group.
Oil specialists said there were ominous signs of US selling in the 'majors'
in recent sessions, partly because of pressure on crude oil prices but, more
importantly, as some of the big US energy funds begin to reshape their
non-US oil portfolios to accommodate Elf's flotation. The French government
intends to sell some 70m Elf shares to raise around Dollars 4.5bn to Dollars
5bn, according to market specialists.
'What is undeniable is that the Elf stock will be priced to go,' said one
oil analyst. He said BP and Shell would be the non-US oil stocks most
vulnerable to US selling. BP lost 3 to 359 1/2 p and Shell 15 to 710p.
