<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow follows lower trend for
bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices followed bonds lower yesterday, in spite of bullish news on
inflation and retail sales, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 6.20 down at 3,842.43. The Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 slipped 1.70 to 472.47, but the American SE composite edged
0.19 higher to 480.06 and the Nasdaq composite firmed 0.94 to 787.81. NYSE
volume amounted to 277.6m shares.
Stocks declined for the third consecutive session even though the day's
economic news was positive for equities. Government figures showed that
consumer prices rose by only 0.2 per cent and retail sales climbed by 0.8
per cent in December. The inflation figure was in line with expectations,
while the retail sales number was stronger than forecast by Wall Street
analysts.
The data should have buoyed stock market sentiment, but investors chose
instead to focus on the decline in bond prices. Longer-dated government
securities fell because of the retail sales figures, which raised fears that
further down the road strong consumer demand might eventually feed through
into higher inflation.
Additionally, analysts said that investors and traders in New York were
unsettled by overnight declines on foreign equity markets, notably Hong
Kong, Frankfurt and London.
Citicorp was the most actively traded issue, rising Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars
40 3/4 , a new 12-month high, in volume of 5.6m shares as the market reacted
positively to news of a restructuring and what should be strong
fourth-quarter earnings.
Another banking stock in demand was JP Morgan, which put on Dollars 3/4 at
Dollars 70 3/8 on news of fourth-quarter profits of Dollars 392m, up from
Dollars 221m a year earlier.
Quaker Oats fell Dollars 3 5/8 to Dollars 65 3/4 after the food group warned
the market that it would report a 15 to 20 per cent decline in fiscal
second-quarter earnings.
Also hit by a profits warning was LA Gear, which dropped Dollars 1 1/8 to
Dollars 8 7/8 after the sports shoe retailer predicted a fourth-quarter loss
on continuing operations of about Dollars 15m, and a full-year deficit of
more than double that.
Bear Stearns rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 23 7/8 after the brokerage house
reported a 110 per cent jump in October-December earnings to Dollars 134.8m,
thanks primarily to sharply higher trading and investment banking revenues.
Canada
Toronto again showed late strength, the TSE 300 index ending at yet another
record high with a rise of 25.2 at 4,479.9. Advances outpaced declines by
443 to 386 after volume of 84.7m shares valued at CDollars 1.1bn. The gold
shares index climbed 1.74 per cent as the Comex bullion price rose on fund
buying. Financial services added 1.51 per cent.
