<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets: India remains on its winning streak -
Budget hopes are fuelling Bombay's rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Indian shares continued their winning streak yesterday, fuelled by foreign
and domestic investors' hopes that next month's budget will give a fresh
impetus to economic growth and to the government's liberalisation programme.
The Bombay Stock Exchange's index of 30 leading shares rose 24.80 to
3,928.59, in the latest upsurge in the market's strongest rally since the
1992 Bombay securities market scandal. The BSE has now advanced almost 50
per cent since the start of November.
The rally has been triggered by foreign fund managers, who have been
permitted to invest in the Indian market for the first time in many years as
part of the economic reform programme. The surge in foreign buying dispelled
the sense of caution that gripped Indian investors in the wake of the 1992
scandal, which ended the previous big rally.
Investors were temporarily knocked out of their stride last month by a
regulatory dispute, which closed the market for two weeks, and by the
political uncertainty caused by the threatened resignation of Mr Manmohan
Singh, the finance minister, who offered to quit after he was criticised by
a parliamentary report into the scandal but was later persuaded to stay.
The effects of these disruptions have proved short-lived. Mr Singh has
emerged from the political turmoil with his reputation enhanced by the
support he received from politicians and businessmen alike.
The regulatory dispute - a row over forward trading between stockbrokers and
the Securities and Exchange Board of India, the markets' watchdog - has yet
to be resolved. But fund managers say they are not unduly concerned by the
argument, as long as it does not lead to another market closure.
The market closed in December when stockbrokers went on strike in protest at
an order from the securities board to liquidate all positions in the forward
market, an order given to stop the market over-heating. The strike ended
after it became clear that the securities board would not relent.
Nor are investors attaching much importance to a separate argument at the
Bombay Stock Exchange which led to the resignation on Monday of Mr GD Desai,
the exchange's president. Mr Desai clashed with exchange board members about
the scope of his powers. His term was due to end in March.
Businessmen in Bombay expect the market to remain strong until the budget,
though they do not rule out temporary corrections. Mr Ajit Dayal, a director
of the Indian affiliate of Jardine Fleming, the investment bank, forecast
the BSE's index would soon cross 4,000. 'Foreign money is piling into the
market,' he said.
Mr Dayal estimated that foreign institutions invested about Dollars 1bn in
the Indian market last year and bought a further Dollars 1.6bn in issues
made by Indian companies overseas. He predicted the combined figure could
reach Dollars 4bn in 1994.
However, more cautious stockbrokers warned that the Finance Ministry is
monitoring the rally closely to avoid any repeat of the 1992 scandal when
funds were illegally siphoned out of the banking system and into equities.
One danger this time is that companies taking advantage of the buoyant
market to raise funds will be tempted to invest the proceeds in the stock
market, possibly breaking securities regulations which restrict such
operations.
The flow of foreign direct investment has also increased sharply. The
Industry Ministry estimates that foreign companies last year invested
Rs16bn, up from Rs6.75bn in 1992. Investments for which approvals were
sought, but which have not necessarily been put into effect yet, increased
to Rs89bn from Rs38.9bn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>INZ  India, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
