<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: French farmers seek flexibility
on trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France's farmers must be given the flexibility by their own government and
the European Union to seek new outlets for products whose export would
otherwise be constrained by last month's settlement of the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade, Mr Luc Guyau, president of FNSEA, the country's
largest farm union, said yesterday.
Farmers should be left free of bureaucratic red tape to upgrade the quality
of food products that could be exported without subsidy and therefore
without Gatt constraints, Mr Guyau said.
The Paris and Brussels authorities should also encourage increased
industrial use of crops to make 'biocarburant' fuel, as well as rewarding
farmers for environmental works like drainage and dykes, which the current
floods in many parts of France had proved inadequate.
Mr Guyau's first press conference of the new year was marked by his
relatively smooth acquiescence in the Gatt deal on terms that until late
last year the FNSEA had denounced as quite unacceptable.
'We are very conscious that we did not get all we hoped for,' he said,
'particularly in terms of a rebalancing of export restrictions with similar
restrictions on imports, and of dealing with monetary fluctuations of the
dollar and within Europe.
'But we have a feeling of pride about our combat over the seven years (of
the Gatt negotiations),' he added.
</TEXT>
