<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: German group to spend Pounds
115m on crop protection programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hoechst and Schering, two of Germany's largest pharmaceutical and chemical
companies, which last month merged their plant protection and pest control
activities, yesterday announced an invest programme of more than DM300m
(Pounds 115m) for crop protection research and development.
At the same time Mr Gerhard Prante, chairman of AgrEvo, the new company,
said increasing its market share in North America and Japan, which he
identified as the two growth areas for pesticides and insecticides, would be
one of its main aims.
AgrEvo will have 1,200 employees at four research centres in Europe: Berlin,
Frankfurt, Paris and Cambridge. They will develop two insecticides and 10
herbicides, which could be registered by the end of the decade.
Until their merger, the agrochemical division of Hoechst, primarily focused
on cereal herbicides and insecticides. Last year it recorded a turnover of
DM2.1bn. Schering, which specialised in sugar beet herbicides, cereal, vine
and fruit fungicides, had a turnover of DM1.3bn. Following the merger,
AgrEvo, which will have its headquarters in Berlin, expects to have a
turnover this year of DM3bn and will employ 8,000 people.
The company already holds 15 per cent of the market share in Europe, 5 per
cent in Japan, and 4.4 per cent in North America. But AgrEvo expects little
growth in Europe this year, because of overcapacity and pressure on
agricultural prices. However, it hopes to expand into eastern Europe despite
the limited purchasing power of the region's farming community, which no
longer enjoys the subsidies of the communist era.
But it is the North American and Asian markets that AgrEvo will home in on
with the intention of developing and marketing the Basta herbicide, a
product designed for compatibility of various crops to glufosinate-ammonium,
a compound that destroys pests.
Essentially, the Basta herbicide enables crops, through molecular biological
processes, to withstand, or have immunity from pesticides and insecticides.
Mr Christoph von Szczepanski, head of research at AgrEvo, said the company
expected to obtain licences for spring-sown oil seed in Canada by 1995. He
added that AgrEvo would introduce to Canada maize, oilseed rape and soyabean
species that would be compatible with the Basta herbicide, making the
company one of the first to market biologically engineered products.
'The aim of the Basta herbicide is not only to maximise yields but to give
farmers greater flexibility in the choice of application time,' said Mr von
Szczepanski.
</TEXT>
