<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: 'American investors fuelled
gold price rise'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A surge in investment demand in North America and parts of Europe helped
boost the gold price last year, says the Gold Fields Mineral Services
consultancy group, in its latest interim report today.
A drop in sales by central banks and other governmental organisations and
less hedging and forward sales by gold producers also contributed to the
price rise.
However, jewellery makers, the most important element of demand in the gold
market, substantially reduced their purchases. There was also a drop in the
buying of gold bars for hoarding.
But jewellery fabrication still accounted for more than all the newly-mined
gold last year, according to GFMS estimates. The supply of newly-mined gold
rose only slightly, by 1.7 per cent, from the 1992 level of 2,231 tonnes to
2,269 tonnes.
GFMS, which has the financial backing of two big gold producers - Gold
Fields of South Africa and Newmont Mining, the largest US gold group - says
that the fall in offtake by the jewellery industry, by 6.8 per cent from
2,675 tonnes in 1992 to an estimated 2,493 tonnes last year, was due in part
to price-sensitivity but also to the effects of economic weakness in Japan
and Europe, the austerity drive in China and the plentiful stocks of gold
that had built up in many Middle Eastern and Far Eastern markets.
Bar hoarding, down more than 32 per cent at 195 tonnes, was similarly
affected by higher prices and a range of local economic factors.
During 1993 the increase in investment demand was quite broadly-based,
suggests GFMS, encompassing the re-appearance of significant private demand
in Germany after the removal of value added tax on financial gold at the
start of the year; the investment in gold futures and over-the-counter
positions by US funds; and the return of Swiss portfolio investment to gold.
'Even if the latter has been primarily on a derivative basis, such as the
purchase of gold call warrants, the impact on demand has been substantial.'
Official sector sales increased not only because some central banks took the
opportunity to sell as prices rose in the second half of 1993 but also
because many of the 'call' options written by central banks earlier in the
year expired 'in the money', resulting in a substantial quantity of the
underlying gold being sold. GFMS estimates net official sales last year were
440 tonnes, nearly one quarter below the 582 tonnes in 1992 but still the
second-highest level of annual sales from this sector since 1979.
The rising price and reduced contangos (forward premiums) persuaded many
producers to allow their forward positions to run down in the second half of
1993. GFMS estimates that forward sales contributed 131 tonnes to supply
last year, a 13 per cent fall from the 150 tonnes in 1992. Option hedging,
after contributing 91 tonnes to supply in 1992, contributed nothing last
year.
Mr Stewart Murray, GFMS chief executive, suggested last night that, compared
with the flat trading in 1992 and the market's overheated state in the
second quarter of 1993, the market now appeared to be returning to
normality. He said the market was entering 1994 'in good shape'.
Gold 1993 - Update II: Pounds 90 or USDollars 145 from GFMS, Greencoat
House, Francis Street, London SW1P 1DH, UK.
