</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / International Company News: Sanyo Securities resists
creditors' restructure plan
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   Emiko Terazono in Tokyo
Sanyo Securities, a second-tier Japanese securities firm, is seeking an
alternative to a restructuring plan recommended by its three main creditor
banks and Nomura Securities, a leading shareholder, without losing their
support. The banks are Bank of Tokyo, Daiwa Bank and Nippon Credit Bank.
The four institutions sent officials into Sanyo to help with a comprehensive
restructuring plan last August. However, the brokerage house has resisted
strong recommendations by the banks to implement drastic rationalisation,
and has not been able to win approval from its creditors.
Sanyo - like other members of the industry - is the victim of the three-year
stock market slump after the large capital investments of the late-1980s
asset 'bubble'. It built a large trading room in a warehouse-like building,
investing heavily in computers and other electronic equipment.
Another source of its problems is Sanyo Sogo Capital, a non-bank financial
affiliate burdened by mounting bad loans. Sanyo Sogo is reported to have
lent Y145bn (Dollars 1.3bn) in real estate-linked deals, of which some Y50bn
have turned sour.
According to the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, a daily business newspaper, the three
banks have extended some Y150bn in loans to Sanyo Sogo, and are also
supplying the cash needed for its daily operations.
'The company is virtually brain-dead,' says Mr David Threadgold, financial
analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd in Tokyo. He expects the three creditors
eventually to bail out Sanyo and its affiliates by agreeing to cut rates on
the loans.
Sanyo Securities expects a pre-tax loss of Y5.7bn for the year to March this
year, but some analysts predict the figure will could be larger due to
financial problems stemming from Sanyo Sogo.
</TEXT>
