<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / International Company News: A tale of debt and survival on
the high seas - How the Atlantic fishery crisis affected two Canadian groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is a tale of two companies which, six years ago, were difficult to tell
apart. However, an unexpected crisis has driven them in almost diametrically
opposite directions, to the point where they now have little in common. One
is brimming with confidence, the other is at the mercy of shareholders and
creditors.
Based in the neighbouring Canadian provinces of Nova Scotia and
Newfoundland, National Sea Products (Natsea) and Fishery Products
International (FPI) were rooted in the rich fishing grounds off Canada's
east coast.
Each was the product of a sweeping rationalisation of the fragmented east
coast fishery in the early 1980s. Their operations were of a similar size,
with each big enough to rank towards the top of the international fishing
industry. Both were vertically integrated, with operations stretching from
impressive trawler fleets to fish-processing plants along the eastern
seaboard of the US and Canada.
There was, however, one big difference between the two companies: debt.
Natsea had its origins in a succession of private-sector takeovers and
mergers. The cornerstone of its 1984 restructuring was a large issue of
preferred shares to creditors. Even when its fishing business was booming in
the mid-80s, its debt was well over 100 per cent of common equity.
FPI had the benefit of being taken under the wing of the Canadian and
Newfoundland governments in the early 1980s. A privatisation deal, including
a CDollars 177m (USDollars 136.2m) public equity issue, was completed just a
few months before the 1987 stock market crash. Its debt as a percentage of
capital at the end of that year was a mere 7.6 per cent.
'We've always said that fish and debt don't mix,' says Mr Victor Young,
FPI's chief executive. 'We've been obsessed with our balance sheet.'
The companies' uneven debt loads have led to sharply different responses to
the virtual disappearance in the late 1980s of the fish on which they
depended. For FPI, the crisis has created an opportunity to diversify.
Debt-burdened Natsea has had little choice but to pull in its horns.
The sudden depletion of cod and other fish stocks in the north-west Atlantic
has yet to be fully explained. Scientists have blamed, among other things,
changes in water temperature and over-fishing by Canadians and Europeans.
In a bid to revive the fishery, the authorities in Ottawa have slashed
groundfish quotas by 75 per cent over the past five years, including a total
ban on catches of northern cod off Newfoundland.
The impact on the local industry has been devastating. About 35,000
fishermen and plant workers are unemployed. Mr Young estimates that FPI has
lost 94 per cent of its north Atlantic fish resource. Natsea's active
fishing fleet, once 50-strong, has been reduced to four vessels, and even
they can put to sea for only a few months each year.
But thanks to its strong balance sheet, FPI has been able to engineer a
transformation from a north Atlantic fishing company to an international
seafood conglomerate.
It has increasingly turned to trading, processing and food-service
operations. FPI bought less than 2 per cent of its raw material from other
parts of the world in the late 1980s; its plants now rely on cod, pollock
and flatfish from as far afield as Russia, Alaska and Scandinavia for 87 per
cent of supplies.
Its customers include British Airways, Scandinavian Airlines and Migros,
Switzerland's leading food retailer.
Revenues have jumped by more than two thirds since 1988, to about CDollars
600m last year. It has made two large acquisitions and is hunting for more.
One acquisition has given the company a toehold in the shrimp business, to
the point where shrimp - most of it bought in the east Asia and sold in the
US - now makes up almost a third of its business.
Natsea's story is a less happy one. Its sales last year were about 40 per
cent below those of 1988. As part of efforts to repair the balance sheet, it
has sold its extensive international operations, which stretched from
Portugal to Australia. Its remaining businesses are centred on the North
American retail market, where its brands remain well-entrenched.
By shrinking, Natsea hopes to rebuild its business from a solid base. 'Our
approach has been to focus on our strengths,' says Mr Henry Demone, Natsea's
president.
FPI's expansion has also given it extra flexibility to deal with remaining
problems at home. One processing plant has been switched from cod to turning
out high-margin shrimp products. The company is negotiating to contribute
some idle trawlers to an international fishing venture, which will help
secure its raw material supplies.
Natsea's gaze, however, remains fixed mostly on its balance sheet. A
considerable write-down will soon be required to take account of the
diminished value of more than a dozen idle vessels and six vacant processing
plants.
Mr Demone's consolation is that, having lost 95 per cent of its Atlantic
fishing quota, Natsea's plight 'obviously can't get much worse'. He is
confident the remaining businesses will be able to support present debt of
between CDollars 80m and CDollars 90m. However, repairing the balance sheet
is likely to require several more years of patience from shareholders and
bankers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>National Sea Products.
    Fishery Products International.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P0912 Finfish.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Market shares.
