<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / International Company News: Investment banking division
helps lift Bear Stearns 110%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bear Stearns, the New York securities house, yesterday announced a 110 per
cent jump in its second fiscal quarter profits to Dollars 134.8m, or Dollars
1.05 a share.
Revenues during the period totalled Dollars 752.1m, up sharply from Dollars
454.7m a year earlier.
The record performance from Bear Stearns, which is the first securities
house to report its profits for the December quarter, suggests the long boom
in earnings on Wall Street is far from over, in spite of the recent upturn
in US interest rates.
Since 1990, declining US interest rates, strong demand from investors for
stocks and bonds, and heavy activity in corporate underwriting and other
investment banking and financial advisory businesses have kept securities
industry profits on a steady upward path.
Bear Stearns said yesterday its record-breaking second quarter was a
reflection of strength in all its main business lines.
Investment banking revenues posted the biggest growth, jumping 180 per cent
from a year ago to Dollars 176.9m as more companies sought the firm's
underwriting and mergers and acquisitions advisory services.
Revenues from principal transactions, which climbed 58 per cent to Dollars
363.4m, remained Bear Stearns' prime source of income, as would be expected
at a firm with a long reputation as an aggressive trading house.
Earnings from brokerage, clearing and private client services rose 23 per
cent to Dollars 129.5m, while interest and dividends brought in Dollars
326.5m.
The firm's total non-interest expenses increased by 51 per cent to Dollars
520.2m, primarily because of a big jump in employee compensation and
benefits, which are tied to business performance.
Investors responded positively to Bear Stearns' earnings report, pushing up
the share price by Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 23 7/8 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</TEXT>
