<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / International Company News: Final quarter puts seal on
strong year at JP Morgan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
J. P. Morgan confounded Wall Street sceptics with record trading income
during the final quarter of 1993, setting the seal on a strong year for the
US bank.
Income from trading in financial markets reached Dollars 606m, compared with
a previous record of Dollars 520m in the second quarter of last year, as
Morgan profited from trading in the emerging country debt markets.
Many had projected that the previous record, set during a time of
instability in European currency and interest rate markets, would be hard to
match.
The trading performance helped push net income in the last three months of
the year to Dollars 392m, or Dollars 1.92 a share, and for the year as a
whole to Dollars 1.72bn, or Dollars 8.48.
Both figures were at the high end of analysts' expectations.
Morgan reported post-tax profits of Dollars 221m, or Dollars 1.10 a share,
for the comparable 1992 quarter, and Dollars 1.13bn, or Dollars 5.66, for
whole of 1992.
Two factors held net income for the period below the third-quarter level in
1993, when it had reached Dollars 468m, or Dollars 2.30.
The bank took a Dollars 120m pre-tax charge to cover property and relocation
costs. Also, revenue described by the bank broadly as 'other non-interest
income' was Dollars 129m lower due to the boost given to the previous period
from a big investment gain.
Sir Dennis Weatherstone, chairman, singled out risk management and emerging
markets as two businesses which had seen 'notable increases' in demand.
For the year as a whole, trading revenues reached Dollars 2.01bn, up from
Dollars 959m the year before, when Morgan took losses from trading
mortgage-backed securities.
Corporate finance revenue rose to Dollars 532m from Dollars 439m,
credit-related fees to Dollars 224m from Dollars 214m, investment management
fees to Dollars 464m from Dollars 377m, operational service fees to Dollars
491m from Dollars 409m and other non-interest revenues to Dollars 406m from
Dollars 164m. By contrast, net gains from investment securities fell to
Dollars 323m from Dollars 388m.
Net interest revenues rose Dollars 64m to Dollars 1.77bn, and it took no
provisions for credit losses during the year, compared with a Dollars 55m
charge in 1992.
</TEXT>
