<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / International Company News: Paramount board backs Dollars
9.7bn bid from QVC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The board of Paramount Communications has recommended that shareholders
reject a controversial Dollars 9.2bn offer for the entertainment company
made last Friday by cable company Viacom and accept a rival Dollars 9.7bn
offer from QVC Network.
The decision, announced on Wednesday night, does not settle the five-month
takeover battle, since shareholders may accept either bid and Viacom could
still make a higher offer by February 1, the date set for final bids.
However, the board's re- endorsement of QVC's offer maintains the
psychological advantage the television home shopping business has enjoyed.
That was when the Paramount board, which had supported a friendly merger
with cable company Viacom, switched sides under pressure from the courts and
said QVC's offer gave shareholders better value.
After Wednesday's board meeting, Mr Martin Davis, Paramount's chairman, did
not address claims by QVC that Viacom's new offer violated the bidding
rules.
However, he said any future bids would continue to be 'rigorously reviewed
with regard to their compliance with the bidding procedures.'
Last Friday night, shortly before QVC's tender offer was due to close,
Viacom announced a new bid which increased from Dollars 85 a share to
Dollars 105 a share the cash it is offering for 50.1 per cent of Paramount's
stock, but sharply cut the value of the securities it is offering in a
'second step merger' for the remaining 49 per cent.
Simultaneously, it announced an Dollars 8.4bn merger agreement with video
rental group Blockbuster Entertainment, which is providing Dollars 1.25bn to
finance the higher cash offer.
The new Viacom bid offers Dollars 13 a share more cash than QVC, but the
total value of its offer is some Dollars 5 a share less than the QVC bid.
</TEXT>
