<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / International Company News: Poland launches 'beauty contest'
for TV licence - Public hearings this weekend may decide the future of
Polish commercial television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI and ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The future shape of Polish commercial television may depend on the outcome
of unprecedented public hearings which begin in Warsaw tomorrow. The
hearings, chaired by Mr Marek Markiewicz, head of the nine-man Television
and Radio Council, the regulatory body, will decide which of 10 competing
foreign and national media groups should be awarded the first Polish
commercial television licence.
The stakes are high. Major international media companies, including
Bertelsmann of Germany, the Compagnie Luxembourgeoise de Telediffusion
(CLT), and Time-Warner of the US, are in the ring.
CLT is linked to Reuters while Time-Warner is harnessed with CNN and Capital
Cities-ABC. Sofirad, a French government-linked company, is running together
with CEDC Media Enterprises, controlled by Mr Mark Palmer, the former US
Ambassador to Budapest. The French pay-TV company, Canal Plus, has put in a
separate bid.
Meanwhile, Top Canal, a local pirate broadcaster, has enlisted the services
of Kinnevik International, the Swedish media group, while Italian interest
is represented by Mr Nicola Grauso. Mr Grauso, a broadcast and print media
owner from Sardinia, obtains some of his programming and advertising from Mr
Silvio Berlusconi's Fininvest group.
The hearings have been designed to give maximum transparency in view of the
potentially lucrative nature of the licence and its political sensitivity.
The proposed new channel will carry news and current affairs programmes as
well as entertainment and sport. It will, therefore, bring an end to
complete political control over the most influential opinion-forming medium
in Poland.
With over 38m inhabitants, Poland is the largest of the post-communist
states of central Europe and the first to emerge from the recession which
followed shock therapy economic reforms. Over 50 per cent of the economy is
now in private hands and 4.5 per cent economic growth is expected for 1994,
after a 4 per cent rise in GNP last year.
Whether the new licence will prove to be 'a licence to print money', as in
the early days of UK commercial TV, however, remains unclear. Last year, the
total advertising spend on Polish TV is estimated by advertising industry
sources at around Dollars 130m.
Industry estimates put the initial investment required to get the proposed
new channel off the ground and running at between Dollars 60m and Dollars
100m. Clauses in the law require that around 50 per cent of broadcast output
is produced locally, so raising costs, while foreign shareholdings in the
competing groups have been limited by law to 33 per cent.
This means that all the international players have had to find local
partners, whose financial resources are in most cases limited.
Another drawback for the successful bidder is that initially the new
'national' channel will reach less than half the potential audience. The
military say they can only free the frequencies needed for nationwide
coverage if they are given funds from the cash-strapped budget to modernise
air traffic control equipment.
Mr Piotr Kolodziejczyk, the defence minister, has said this could take up to
three years. Such a delay means that the new channel will face losses of
revenue to local and regional TV stations, which are also applying for
licences and whose applications are to be decided at a later date.
The problem with frequencies could possibly be resolved sooner if President
Lech Walesa, who is responsible for defence, was better disposed towards the
broadcasting council.
However, the council has already infuriated the President by appointing Mr
Wieslaw Walendziak, an independent-minded, 31-year old journalist to head
state-owned TV.
The decision led Mr Walesa publicly to call for the resignation of Mr
Markiewicz, as well as two colleagues nominated by him last year. The three
refused to resign and the row has since died down, but it showed how
precarious the council's position is.
Mr Markiewicz, the council's chairman, is a soft-spoken, 42-year old lawyer
from Lodz who represented the Solidarity trade union in the last parliament.
He tends to pick his words with the thoughtful attention of a man who knows
he is in a political minefield.
The council was originally appointed last year by the president and the
former Parliament. Its members were chosen from the 29 parties represented
in the old parliament, which reflected all strands of political opinion in
the country.
Despite their differing political origins, the council members have
developed an esprit de corps. But they no longer reflect the political
realities of the recently elected current parliament. The September
elections eliminated most of the smaller parties and parliament is now
dominated by a centre-left coalition with its roots in the communist past.
In March, the council will present its first annual report to parliament.
Should this be rejected, its members will have to resign. As the council is
charged not only with granting licences but also monitoring broadcasting
activity, the implications for media freedom and the future of the proposed
commercial channel are serious.
So far, the government has been careful not to back President Walesa in his
attempts to get Mr Markiewicz replaced. However, as Mr Leszek Miller, the
labour minister who is attuned to feeling on the left wing of the ruling
Left Democratic Alliance (SLD), says: 'President Walesa has put the thought
that Markiewicz and his colleagues might be replaced into people's minds, so
who knows?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
