<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Matthew Clark draws benefit from
acquisitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first benefits from acquisitions made in 1993 lifted interim pre-tax
profits of Matthew Clark, the drinks producer and wholesaler, by 42 per cent
from Pounds 2.42m to Pounds 3.43m.
Four months' trading from Freetraders, the drinks wholesaler, and one week
from Grants of St James's, the wine business, accounted for Pounds 24m of
total turnover of Pounds 47.6m (Pounds 26.1m) and contributed Pounds 1.16m
to operating profits of Pounds 3.57m (Pounds 2.45m).
Continuing operations had shown only slight growth during the six months to
end-October, said Mr Peter Aikens, chief executive. 'Once again the build up
to the Christmas trade was slower than we would prefer but we recorded a
strong spurt in sales in December itself, although margins remained under
acute pressure in the branded drinks division'.
Freetraders' performance had been 'most encouraging,' he said. In its year
to end-September, it had achieved organic growth of 18.9 per cent in sales
and 25.6 per cent in operating profits. But the group's total wholesaling
business still represented only 1 per cent of the pubs, hotels and
restaurants market.
Integration of the Grants business was proceeding to plan and would produce
significant cost savings, Mr Aikens said. Redundancy notices were issued
yesterday to 225 of the 540-strong workforce and a production unit at
Worksop has been closed.
Sales of Strathmore spring water - an earlier acquisition in the buying
spree that has quadrupled the size of the group in the last three years -
increased 20 per cent by volume in a market which grew overall by 10 per
cent. Further investment is being made in marketing support to widen
distribution.
Overall British wine volumes were marginally lower but the group's main
brands maintained their position in a market in which commodity products
made large inroads into the own label business.
Earnings were 16p (15.2p) and the interim dividend is lifted to 7.25p
(6.75p).
</TEXT>
