<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Wyko loss grows to Pounds 0.3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Falls in turnover and margins in UK manufacturing and losses in South Africa
left Wyko, the West Midlands manufacturer and distributor of bearings and
power transmission components, with increased interim pre-tax losses.
The board has decided to pass the interim dividend, against last time's
0.5p.
Mr Philip White, chairman, warned that although trading was expected to
improve during the second half, all of the exceptional costs involved in
scaling down the manufacturing operations would be taken in this year's
accounts.
The loss for the six months to October 31 was Pounds 333,000 against a
profit of Pounds 121,000.
The group's fortunes slipped during the second half of 1992-93 and the year
ended with a deficit of Pounds 20,000.
There was an operating loss in UK manufacturing of Pounds 432,000, including
redundancy costs of Pounds 116,000. The South African activities, which were
sold earlier this month, recorded a loss of Pounds 103,000.
In UK manufacturing there has been a drive against costs, including the
merger of three businesses into one and a reduction in staffing. The group
payroll, 1,120 two years ago, is now 915 and will be down to about 850 by
the end of the rationalisation programme next May.
The international distribution business, however, is performing strongly and
UK distribution is seeing recovery in demand.
After a tax charge of Pounds 50,000 (Pounds 145,000) losses per share were
1.19p (0.07p). For the full year there were losses of 0.5p, when total
dividend payments came to 1p.
Turnover was slightly higher at Pounds 30.4m (Pounds 29m). However operating
profits slumped to Pounds 96,000 (Pounds 685,000), which was not enough to
cover interest payments of Pounds 429,000 (Pounds 424,000), reflecting
gearing of 62 per cent.
