<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Gartmore launches split capital investment
trust
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gartmore is launching a new split capital investment trust, the British
Income and Growth Trust, via an offer for subscription opening on February
15.
There will be two classes of shares: ordinary income, with a predicted
dividend yield of 9.3 per cent; and zero dividend preference shares, with a
forecast annualised gross redemption yield of 8 per cent. Packaged units,
yielding 4.4 per cent, are also available.
The trust will invest in UK shares with higher than average yields, though
not always the highest yielding, to allow greater diversification. The trust
is due to be wound up at the end of 2002. It will need to achieve growth of
5 per cent a year if income shares are to be repaid with no loss of capital,
and an annual yield of 140 per cent of the FT-SE-A All-Share to cover all
charges as well as predicted yields on income shares and packaged units.
Mr Lewis McNaught, of Gartmore Fund Managers, said he expected strong demand
for the zeros from institutions, and for the income shares from private
investors looking for Pep investments ahead of the tax year end.
Mr John Szymanowski, an investment trust analyst at SG Warburg, said the
trust was very similar to Gartmore's Shared Equity trust, which had a
slightly higher yield. Shared Equity was launched in November as a result of
the restructuring of Gartmore Value. Mr McNaught said that interest shown in
that launch had prompted the development of the new fund with an almost
identical structure.
Launch expenses will be capped at 4 per cent, and the annual management
charge will be 0.5 per cent. Pep charges will be 1 per cent initially and
0.75 per cent annually.
</TEXT>
