<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Absence of exceptionals leaves Cray Elect
lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An underlying 10 per cent increase in turnover and improved trading margins
helped Cray Electronics Holdings, the data communications and software
systems group, double interim operating profits from continuing operations
to Pounds 9.6m, against Pounds 4.79m.
However, pre-tax profits in the six months to October 31 fell to Pounds
7.8m, after Pounds 1.12m in reorganisation costs, compared with Pounds
17.8m, swollen by a Pounds 13m exceptional gain on the sale of Malvern
Instruments.
Earnings per share from continuing operations increased to 3.1p (2.04p), but
fell on an FRS 3 basis to 2.52p (10.33p). The interim dividend is 0.75p
(0.5p).
The figures were in line with expectations, but the market focused on the
headline pre-tax figure and the shares slipped 6 1/2 p to close at 164 1/2
p.
Turnover, including a Pounds 5.22m contribution from P-E International
acquired for Pounds 16.2m in September and Pounds 396,000 (Pounds 11.7m)
from discontinued activities, increased to Pounds 114.3m (Pounds 81.9m).
The figure was boosted by higher overseas sales, particularly in the US and
Asia Pacific regions, and by a full contribution from the Dowty IT
businesses which were acquired in August 1992.
P-E contributed Pounds 32,000 to operating profits while the discontinued
Shrewsbury Technology operations incurred a Pounds 780,000 loss. Last year
discontinued operations showed a Pounds 919,000 profit.
Mr Roger Holland, chairman said: 'We have improved revenue, profit and
operating margin in our principal businesses. The growth we have experienced
outside the UK is particularly pleasing.'
The advance in operating profits and the overall trading margins, which
increased from 6.8 per cent to 8.8 per cent, was led by Cray Communications
which accounted for almost 70 per cent of turnover.
The division lifted operating profits to Pounds 7.8m (Pounds 3.1m) while
margins improved from 7.3 per cent to 10.4 per cent. It was helped by the
strong demand for integrated local and wide area networking systems, and the
introduction of new products.
Cray Systems, which now includes P-E International's computer services
operations, reported operating profits of Pounds 1.2m (Pounds 900,000) while
Cray Technology slipped from Pounds 800,000 to Pounds 600,000.
COMMENT
Cray's management deserves credit for the detail and openness of the interim
figures which included an illuminating breakdown of Pounds 4.2m in fair
value adjustments following the P-E acquisition which has already helped the
systems division achieve critical mass. The core communications division has
a strong product portfolio in a dynamic growth sector and is aiming to lift
margins to 20 per cent over the next few years. A traditionally stronger
second half should lift full year pre-tax profits to Pounds 26m for earnings
of about 8.8p. The shares are trading on a prospective p/e of 18.7.
</TEXT>
