<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Metals group gives ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Metallgesellschaft, the stricken German metals, mining and industrial group,
gave ground to creditor banks yesterday, relaxing its uncompromising stance
on the DM3.4bn (Pounds 1.32bn) refinancing proposals.
Amid frantic negotiations on both sides of the Atlantic, Metallgesellschaft
reached an agreement with Norddeutsche Landesbank, the German public sector
bank which had denounced the terms.
But although the concessions wrung from the Frankfurt-based conglomerate are
to be offered to all banks, the modified proposals were not enough to win
over French banks who formed a new centre of resistance. Officials from
Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank, Germany's two biggest banks and
shareholders in Metallgesellschaft, flew to Paris yesterday afternoon to
hold talks with French creditors, including Societe Generale, Credit
Lyonnais and Banque Paribas.
Representatives of French banks gathered at Societe Generale's Paris
headquarters to outline their objections. French banks are believed to be
owed about one fifth of the near DM5bn lent by 120 banks.
Metallgesellschaft, whose shares were suspended yesterday, said it would not
be able to make a statement on the response to the refinancing plans before
Saturday. Neither the company nor Deutsche Bank would comment on details of
the concessions won by Nord LB. The original proposals envisaged a DM1.4bn
rights issue, the conversion of DM1.3bn of bank debt into junior convertible
stock and DM700m of new credit lines.
The company's willingness to make concessions represents a big shift in its
position. It had threatened to declare itself insolvent if the proposals
were not accepted in their entirety. But the Wednesday deadline slipped by
and many banks simply regarded the statement as a tough negotiating
position.
Protests focused on the terms of the debt conversion and the requirement for
bank creditors to contribute to the rights issue. Societe Generale argued
that the main shareholders, including Deutsche Bank, Dresdner Bank and the
Allianz insurance group, should 'play a larger part'.
Management, Page 17
World stock markets, Page 37
