<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Bundesbank fails to halt dollar rise after US retail surge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE and GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A bigger-than-expected increase in US retail sales last month pushed the
dollar up sharply yesterday in spite of Bundesbank intervention.
Retail sales rose 0.8 per cent last month and by 6.9 per cent in the year to
December, the Commerce Department said. Most economists had expected a
December rise of only about 0.3 per cent and the figures caused economists
to revise upwards their estimates of US fourth-quarter economic growth.
Separate inflation figures showed a rise in the consumer price index of 0.2
per cent last month and 2.7 per cent in the year to December, roughly in
line with projections.
Many Wall Street analysts have raised their estimate of growth in the fourth
quarter to an annual rate of 5 per cent or slightly more. But most expect
growth to moderate this quarter.
Nevertheless, the figures caused the dollar to break through its 1993 high
of DM1.7480, and then breach a second key market barrier of DM1.7520. The
dollar closed in London at DM1.752, up nearly 2 pfennigs on its Tokyo
overnight level. In New York it finished at DM1.7513.
The Bundesbank's attempt to defend the D-Mark against the dollar was the
first for at least seven months, dealers said.
After rumours of Bundesbank intervention swept the European markets in the
morning, the Bundesbank bought D-Marks worth 'several hundred million
dollars', according to one dealer, in an attempt to hold the dollar at
DM1.7440.
Mr John LaWare, a Federal Reserve governor, said he saw little reason for an
early adjustment of monetary policy. 'The inflation outlook is favourable,'
he told business people in Boston. He predicted the annual rate of inflation
would stay in the 2.7-2.8 per cent range this year.
The Fed expected the economy to grow by 3-3.5 per cent this year after
expanding at an unsustainable annual rate of 5 per cent in the fourth
quarter, he said.
Some analysts cautioned that the retail sales figures were less robust than
they appeared, especially after adjustments for a fourth-quarter surge in
car sales.
Mr Edward McKelvey, a senior economist at investment bank Goldman Sachs,
said the momentum of consumer demand probably slowed as the economy moved
into the first quarter of this year, despite strong figures for December
sales. Goldman predicts real economic growth will decline to an annual rate
of 2 per cent by the second quarter.
Government bonds, Page 29
Currencies, Page 31
US stocks, Page 37
