<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: Siemens
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The 5 per cent fall in Siemens' shares yesterday is nothing compared to the
rough treatment given to Alcatel-Alsthom following its profits warning on
Wednesday. Yet Siemens now stands 9 per cent below the peak reached at the
turn of the year, which underlines how far stock market valuations have run
ahead of earnings prospects. There are bright spots in yesterday's
statement, such as the prediction that semiconductors will return to profit
by 1995 and the promise of reduced losses at Siemens Nixdorf this year. The
snag is that loss elimination will be offset by declining profits elsewhere.
Like Alcatel-Alsthom, one of Siemens' most profitable divisions is starting
to suffer as European governments cut spending on telecommunications. That
squeeze on new orders and margins is worst on Siemens' home turf. Income
from its large investment portfolio, which helped maintain profits in
1992-93, is also in decline. While the impact of lower interest rates and
bond yields is impossible to predict, though, there are signs that dwindling
investment income is spurring management to tackle the operational problems.
The promise of 10,000 job cuts this year - around 2.5 per cent of the
workforce - is a step in that direction. More of the same would help support
the shares at the lower level now established. The lingering danger for
shareholders is that Siemens feels obliged to spread the pain and cut its
dividend as well. Since the pay-out was last raised in 1990, and then only
by 50 pfennigs, a cut at this stage would be especially cruel.
