<PROFILE>_AN-EANDNAEHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Leading Article: Mr Clinton's trade agenda
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
With the passage of the North American Free Trade Agreement and the
completion of the Uruguay Round of multilateral trade negotiations, Mr
Clinton has finished the trade agenda he inherited. This is a great
achievement. But now he must draw up his own. The signs so far are worrying.
He seems to be dedicating his country to distorting trade, where it will not
merely end up restricting it.
One part of the Clinton agenda already in effect is its approach to the
opening of Japanese markets. The objective is right. But the administration
is proposing the wrong instrument and the wrong procedures.
American policymakers protest that the quantitative indicators they propose
are neither targets nor of benefit to US exporters alone. They protest too
much. The semiconductor pact has shown that an indicator is a target by
another name. Similarly, the Japanese are bound to satisfy US producers
first, because they are the most powerful. Since cartelisation and
administrative guidance are needed for Japanese industry to deliver the
demanded results, the US administration is also, in effect, calling for
reregulation and deregulation at the same time.
What is wrong with the chosen procedures is that they are unilateral. If US
policymakers are confident they can prove that the Japanese cheat, they
should bring their complaint to a multilateral forum. As it is, they have
agreed to the creation of a world trade organisation within the Uruguay
Round settlement, but are managing their most important trade relationship
bilaterally. Faced with yet another contradiction, the Japanese must wonder
why occidentals are so inscrutable.
Distorting trade
If this approach to Japan threatens to distort trade, the emerging US agenda
for post-Uruguay Round trade negotiations may end up by simply restricting
it. Mr Clinton suggested this week that environmental protection, anti-trust
regulation and labour standards should be at the top of the agenda.
International agreement on competition policy is needed, particularly if the
cancer of anti-dumping is to be brought under control. But the other
suggestions could easily become excuses for outright protectionism. The
question of desirable standards is far more complex than most western
lobbyists and governments are prepared to admit.
Consider the environment. It is untrue that trade necessarily harms the
environment, that all countries ought to have the same environmental
regulations, that differences in environmental regulation are bound to
create unfair competititive advantages, or even that the chief global
environmental threat is posed by the development of poorer countries. US
policymakers and lobbyists would do well to remember, for example, that the
profligate 15 per cent of humanity emit far more greenhouse gases than do
the remaining 85 per cent.
Labour quagmire
Labour standards are an equally sticky quagmire. It is not true, for
example, that wages are low in China because of exploitation, but because
the country remains dreadfully poor. It is not true that wages in high
productivity factories should be far higher than elsewhere, because it is
their profits that fuel rapid development. It is also not true that sensible
minimum labour standards would eliminate the competitive threat supposedly
posed by cheap labour. Remember, above all, that high minimum wages are of
no benefit to the hundreds of millions of unemployed, while laws against
child labour are of no help to children who would otherwise starve.
The danger is that this supposedly high-minded agenda would punish the poor
for their poverty. The side agreements on labour and the environment in
Nafta do little to assuage that fear. Consider, for example, the fact that
participants may not lower any standards, however inappropriate and costly
they may turn out to be. Yet it is these agreements which are the model that
the administration seems to want to spread throughout the world.
What the Clinton administration's agenda lacks is a commitment to
liberalisation. It seems to see the emerging global market economy as a
threat to be curbed, not an opportunity to be exploited. International
standards will form part of the trade agenda. But they must be only a small
part.
</TEXT>
