<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: Private rail operators will compete
with low fares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ROGER FREEMAN, MP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, You reported a BR manager's claim that there is a threat to discounted
fares on off-peak railway services on the new franchised passenger routes
('Rail sell-off threatens to limit scope of discount fares', January 13).
BR will have no part to play, however, in the setting of franchised service
discount ticketing levels except where it wins a franchise itself. The new
private sector operators will be extremely keen to attract the maximum
number of passengers to their routes. As has been the experience in other
transport fields, they will not achieve that by raising prices but by
offering their own discounts to tempt new passengers.
If BR finds it commercially sensible to offer discounted tickets, which it
does at present without any compulsion, you can expect the private sector to
be even keener.
A balance has to be struck between the convenience of commonly priced
inter-available tickets and the possibility of a wider choice of differently
priced services. Inter-availability and common pricing of tickets will
normally be a requirement of franchise agreements for season and full-fare
standard and first-class tickets on shared routes.
Discounted travel, even now, does not offer unrestricted travel. Off-peak
fares attract their own conditions limiting travel to particular trains,
days and times. The present success of Apex fares shows that many passengers
are prepared to accept restrictions on their time of travel to benefit from
cheaper fares, and I am sure that such passengers will benefit from allowing
operators to compete for their custom with discounted fares.
Roger Freeman,
minister for public transport,
Department of Transport,
2 Marsham Street,
London SW1P 3EB
</TEXT>
