FT  14 JAN 94 / Letters to the Editor: The regulation insurance needs (1)
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr M G NEWMARCH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your leader, 'An end to foot-dragging' (January 12), proposes that I
may underestimate the challenge facing the insurance industry. Your
proposition astounds me.
It is precisely because I recognise the need for the industry to eliminate
bad sales and marketing practices - in the common interest of the consumer
and reputable life offices - that I reject as unworkable the current
proposals for reform on the basis of the Large report and Personal
Investment Authority.
For some 18 months now, the Prudential has argued that such is the wholly
unsatisfactory state of retail financial services regulation that the
experiment of 'self-regulation within a statutory framework' be admitted a
failure by the appropriate authorities. We advocate the appointment of an
independent committee of inquiry chaired by a senior judicial or legal
figure with an unrestricted brief to redefine the objectives of saver
protection and the statutory and institutional framework best suited to
achieve that.
Each day that passes confirms us in our view that the only likely way to
achieve those acceptable standards of protection due to the nation's savers
is by such a route, which implies single-tier statutory regulation with
direct accountability to Parliament.
M G Newmarch,
chief executive,
Prudential Corporation,
142 Holborn Bars,
London EC1N 2NH
