<TEXT>
Sir, Hugh Carnegy ('Struggle to square the Arctic circle', January 6), in
his review of Swedish attitudes to membership of the European Union,
understates the party political dimension of the debate in Sweden. The
decline in support for the 'Yes' campaign has taken place primarily among
Social Democrat supporters confused by the party leadership's decision to
await the outcome of the negotiations before formally campaigning for
membership.
I, too, have stood in the snow and dark of Arctic farms in Norrbotten and I
have no doubt that the European Union will accept the case for continued
regional and social subsidies. With the successful conclusion of
negotiations on March 1, I have every hope that the Social Democrat party
will overcome its tactical coyness and will campaign in public for the
membership to which its leaders are privately committed.
