<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Arts: Piano duo par excellence - Concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two pianists on a single concert platform, whether performing on one
instrument or two, tend to be assigned to the fringes of the musical
profession. The dazzling qualities of Yaara Tal and Andreas Groethuysen,
whose recital at the Wigmore Hall on Wednesday formed their London debut,
helped shed new light on why this general marginalising process has come
about, and why - at least on such occasions as this - it can seem so
wastefully unjust.
The domestic background to the two-pianist performance tradition has much to
do with it (before the arrival of the gramophone, the transcription of
orchestral and operatic works for four pianistic hands was the most popular
way of disseminating them throughout the the music-loving public). But too
often, once the novelty has worn off, the concert-hall pairings of even the
most celebrated pianists can prove more enjoyable for the executants than
for the audience.
Not this time. The European reputation of this young team preceded them here
 -the Israeli Tal and the German Groethuysen have been working together for
eight years, with already six records on the Sony label to their credit. The
pleasures of listening to them on Wednesday, in an entirely four-hand,
single-keyboard programme, revealed themselves as exactly those of the best
chamber-music-making: all freak elements of muscularity, gymnastic display
and co-ordinated trickery had been purged from the experience.
These two are both superb individual artists - Tal sparkles on the higher
lines, Groethuysen's suave yet solid tones amply fill out the lower - whose
personalities and characteristics contrast and balance each other with
satisfying exactitude. As in the best chamber-musical team-work, the highest
degree of ensemble co-ordination can be taken for granted: it is always
directed outwards, beyond the frissons of the immediate moment.
They opened with a 'display' sonata (in C minor, Op. 10) by Czerny, the
Beethoven pupil and noted piano pedagogue. What might in other circumstances
have sounded merely facile and flash was here continually exquisite, bold
and charming. In Schubert's F minor Fantasia their delicacy of sculpted
phrasing and expertise in range of dynamics could perhaps be criticised for
diluting the essential ruggedness of the invention. On the other hand, it
was not wilting, languid delicacy and expertise, and it touched veins of
pathos in the music rarely even hinted.
After the interval Brahms's 16 Waltzes, Op. 39, mounted a catalogue of
melodic verve exactly tempered by rhythmic subtlety. The finale, an
unattributed transcription of Mendelssohn's C minor Piano Trio, Op. 66,
summed up every quality that had made the recital so rewarding, and added
thereto a controlled large-scale bravura that sent one out of the hall on a
cloud of happiness and elation. I cannot wait to hear this duo again.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7929 Entertainers and Entertainment Groups.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT941-15536</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EANDNADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Arts: Into the mind of Modigliani - William Packer admires
the collection of largely unknown drawings at the Royal Academy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM PACKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The life of Modigliani too often gets in the way of the work, especially a
life so tragically romantic as his - the doomed, dissolute, handsome artist,
unrecognised by the world and dead too soon. What his drawings tell us,
however, is that whatever else he was or did, he kept a clear creative
intelligence, responding critically to all that he saw about him and
resolving it into something unmistakably his own.
Last year, at the Palazzo Grassi in Venice, more than 400 drawings by
Modigliani went on public show for the first time. It was certainly the
exhibition of the year, if not the decade. Paul Alexandre was Modigliani's
doctor first, then his friend. From the time of the artist's arrival in
Paris in 1906, at the age of 22, until his own departure for the war in
1914, Dr Alexandre acquired every drawing by Modigliani that he could lay
hands on. The two men never met again and Modigliani died of TB in the
January of 1920. Dr Alexandre lived on until 1968, ever cherishing the
intention of publishing his collection along with a memoir of his
relationship with Modigliani. It has fallen to his son, Noel, to realise, at
last, the paternal ambition.
The scope of the collection is the surprise and revelation, more than
doubling as it does the published canon of the artist's graphic oeuvre, and
transforms our understanding of his work overall. The Alexandre collection
now comes to London not in its entirety, but in a selection, made by Mary
Anne Stevens of the Royal Academy, of some 240 drawings.
This substantial reduction is both welcome and regrettable. Drawing is a
special and often recondite study and those 400 sheets and more of
Modigliani, the mass of them insistently repetitive, were quite enough to
daunt even the most committed of connoisseurs.
While requiring still the closest critical attention, what seemed in Venice
perhaps too severe and exhausting an exercise, should be, in London, so much
more readily accessible to a general audience. At 240 or so, nothing of the
scope of the collection has been sacrificed; and yet that insistent, testing
repetition was, for me at least, rather the point.
Swings and roundabouts I suppose.
The signal importance of the collection lies in what it tells us, in
intimate detail, of Modigliani's development in his work from the first
flowering of his talent to the period of its full maturity. It is a period
marked by what once seemed abrupt shifts and transitions, in practice as in
interest: from painting to sculpture and back to painting; from the direct
observation of the figure to an extreme stylisation, based on tribal and
classical examples, and back again. What we are now able to see and realise
 -and I must emphasise that we may do so just as well in Dr Stevens'
selection as in the full feast - is that those transitions were not abrupt
at all, but natural, consistent and inevitable, the work all of a piece.
Here is the young man, looking now at Lautrec, now at the more decorative
expressionism of the Secession, now at the harder expressionism of the
Germans, now at the symbolism of early Picasso, with his clowns and
saltimbanques. But then the image of the figure is sharpened and simplified
into something more sculptural. The form may place him close to Brancusi,
but yet these kneeling caryatids with their swayed hips and shoulders, for
all that they carry the world on their shoulders, are clearly drawn not by
invention but from the model in the studio.
Even the severest of the busts, the most rigid of the standing figures,
carry with them the sense not of the remote and abstracted image, carved in
stone, but of the living model, flesh and blood. And so it is that the
reversion back to painting, to the portraits and the spectacular late
reclining nudes, done long after Dr Alexandre had gone off to the War, come
as no surprise at all. It is rather those sculptural qualities, there all
the time, that are now the surprise.
The line dances down the contour, with the merest inflexion this way or
that. The touch is by turns light, heavy, simple, subtle, crude - so
deceptively crude. There it is, conjured out of the barest outline, the
palpable human presence in all its weight and volume and living movement.
Wonderful.
The Unknown Modigliani: Royal Academy of Arts, Piccadilly W1, until April 4.
Then on to Cologne, Bruges, Tokyo, Mexico, Luxembourg, Montreal, New York,
Madrid and Rouen; sponsored in London by Glaxo and The Guardian.
</TEXT>
<XX>
