<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stage mothers are bad enough, but rink mothers sound worse. Short Stories
reports on 'the Jemettes', junior European precision skating champions, who
are practising for a competition in Sweden and for their appearance in 'The
Sleeping Beauty'.
The mothers of these budding Torvills and Deans sew the sequins and bull the
skating boots (8.00 C4).
Further Abroad is a genuinely eccentric series, which makes a change after
all those mannered programmes where arm waving egotists with odd accents
strain desperately for eccentricity.
Jonathan Meades doesn't need to strain: he is really weird.
Tonight his subject is architecture in the context of brewing (9.30 BBC2).
Two middle-of-the-road drama series return. In The Chief Martin Shaw is now
the chief constable of 'Eastland', a role originally played by Tim
Piggott-Smith. Today's plot involves illegal immigrants (9.00 ITV).
In Love Hurts Adam Faith plays a rich plumber and Zoe Wanamaker a pushy
middle class administrator, working for a big charity (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
