<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / People: Confederation of British Industry
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, Elizabeth Haywood, the European affairs manager at the WDA, is
moving to the Confederation of British Industry in Wales to succeed Ian
Kelsall, its long-serving director.
At the WDA she has a team of 12 people developing and co-ordinating the
agency's policy on Europe and has been responsible for programmes to
increase the involvement of small and medium-sized Welsh enterprises in
European markets, especially by encouraging strategic alliances.
Before joining the WDA four years ago, Haywood, who is 38, worked for the
European parliament in Luxembourg and Brussels and gained a doctorate in
French politics at University College, Swansea.
She will take up the post in March. 'My aim is to ensure a strong identity
for Welsh business and industry, and I plan to further the already strong
links between CBI Wales and the WDA to achieve this,' she says.
Kelsall decided to retire last autumn after 28 years as director, during
which time he became one of the best-known businessmen in Wales. On a
half-time basis, he has since become director of Merthyr Tydfil Business
Centre, which has been set up to encourage the town's economic growth.
</TEXT>
