<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Ringing in a new lightweight
phone
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nokia, the Finnish mobile phone manufacturer, this month launches what it
claims is the smallest and lightest mobile phone for the new digital
networks springing up worldwide, writes Andrew Adonis.
Weighing less than 200 grams with a special lightweight battery, the Nokia
2110 'family' offers the same basic design and features for Europe's GSM and
PCN networks, the American TDMA standard and the emerging Japanese Digital
Phone System.
It intensifies competition in the market for digital handsets, the high
price of which is one of the main obstacles to the growth of digital
networks in countries - such as the UK - with mature analogue networks.
Nokia is likely to launch the 2110 on the UK market at a price competitive
with existing Siemens and Motorola digital handsets, which retail at between
Pounds 250 and Pounds 300. Nokia Mobile Phones: UK, 480 434343.
</TEXT>
