<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / People: Non-executive directors
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lionel Stammers, who resigned from BTR last month, is joining the board of
TOMKINS, another acquisitive conglomerate. Stammers, 60, is one of three
non-executives joining a boardroom which has traditionally been dominated by
executive directors.
Apart from Stammers, whose 29 years at BTR covered its growth from a stock
market minnow into Britain's ninth biggest company, Jim Butler, 64, a former
senior partner of KPMG Peat Marwick, and David Crowe, 54, a former senior
partner of Gouldens, the city law firm, are joining Tomkins' board on March
1.
Crowe is currently an executive director of TT Group, a small conglomerate
which, like Tomkins, was set up by a former head of acquisitions at Hanson.
Crowe's old law firm is Hanson's legal adviser.
Greg Hutchings, Tomkins' chief executive, says that his three new non-execs
will bring different things to the boardroom. In Stammers' case it is his
operational skills. Crowe's legal expertise will help ensure that Tomkins
complies with the Cadbury committee recommendations and Butler will advise
on accounting standards and internal control (See Observer).
</TEXT>
