<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / People: Provident move to RBS venture
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ian Chippendale is to head up a new insurance venture which will seek to
emulate the success of Direct Line, the rapidly growing 'direct' motor
insurer owned by the Royal Bank of Scotland. Royal Bank announced its plans
to launch the new company, which will specialise in sales of non-standard
motor and home policies, last November.
Chippendale, 45, has been an executive director at Provident Financial, a
successful consumer credit and insurance company, since 1989. Chippendale
held responsibility for the group's operating companies in the insurance
sector - including Halifax Insurance, a motor insurance underwriter which
specialises in women drivers, and Colonnade Insurance Brokers, a chain of
registered brokers - as well as overall responsibility for the group's
corporate development. Chippendale will work closely with Peter Wood, the
founder of Direct Line, who will be non-executive chairman of the new
company. It will be launched before the end of the year and initially will
be based in Leeds.
Wood will invest Pounds 1m and own 40 per cent of the new company, with
Royal Bank investing Pounds 1.5m to acquire 60 per cent of the ordinary
equity and a further Pounds 22.5m in preference shares.
Chippendale's appointment was announced at the Royal Bank's agm in Edinburgh
yesterday where shareholders approved with only one dissenting vote a deal
which replaces Peter Wood's controversial bonus arrangement with the bank.
Wood, who received Pounds 18m last year, is to be paid a lump sum of Pounds
17m plus a contribution of Pounds 7m to his pension. He has also bought
Pounds 7.5m worth of shares in the Royal Bank of Scotland.
