<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Technology: Making monoclonal antibodies
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The first step is to inject a mouse with a disease-causing agent and extract
antibody-producing cells from its spleen. These are fused in the laboratory
with myeloma (cancer) cells to make hybridomas - immortal antibody-producing
cells that grow and divide indefinitely in a fermentation tank. One
hybridoma can produce billions of clones, all producing the same monoclonal
antibodies. Such antibodies have occasionally been used on their own to
activate the body's natural cell-killing mechanism. But researchers usually
make them more lethal by linking them to a poison molecule or to a
radioactive isotope.
</TEXT>
