<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Survey of Drax - The Big Clean-up (9): State-of-the-art
technology - German experience with FGDs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA KNIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the early 1980s, reports of forests dying from acid rain pollution were
horrifying the German public. Power stations were soon identified as a
leading culprit and the West German government reacted swiftly by passing
the Large Combustion Plant Ordinance (LCPO) in July 1983. A massive FGD
programme began.
No other country in the world has carried out a power station
desulphurisation programme remotely comparable with that in West Germany
during the years 1983 to 1988.
The Ordinance laid down strict sulphur dioxide emissions limits for existing
and new plant and all large West German power stations using fossil fuels
were retrofitted with desulphurisation plant over this five-year period.
Today, SO emissions from power stations have been reduced to just 10 per
cent of the volume emitted in 1982. In 1991, specific SO output from coal
and oil power stations in Germany was by far the lowest in Europe at 0.92 gm
per kWh. Thus Germany already easily fulfils the European Community
directive passed in 1988 on large combustion plant. This requires a
reduction in SO emissions in Germany of 40 per cent by 1993, 60 per cent by
1988; and 70 per cent by 2003, compared with 1980 levels.
The EC directive required that only new power stations were fitted with
desulphurisation plant. Retrofitting of old plant was not obligatory and has
only been carried out in Germany.
The German Utilities Association in Frankfurt, VDEW, says DM15bn was spent
on the big desulphurisation campaign - while a further DM7bn was invested in
de-NOX plant - over the period 1983 to 1988 in Germany.
The annual expenditure on FGD operation, including serving capital costs,
amounts to some DM3.5bn. This adds 1.5 to 2.0 pfennig per kWh to the cost of
electricity generation. For comparison, in mid-1993, industrial customers
were paying an average 19.74 pfennigs per kWh for their electricity, not
including the average 7.5 per cent German coal support levy.
German unification has resulted in a new wave of FGD retrofitting in eastern
Germany, to large power stations which burn brown coal. A total of eight
500MW units at Boxberg and Jaenschwalde will have desulphurisation plant
installed. The other 8,000MW of brown coal-fired capacity will have to be
closed down by the end of June 1996 - the LCPO deadline applied to eastern
Germany.
How necessary this new desulphurisation campaign had become is illustrated
by the fact that in 1990 East German SO emissions were 1.84m tonnes; 10
times higher than those in West Germany although electricity production in
the east was just one tenth of that in the west.
In practice, German coal power station operators use almost exclusively the
so-called limestone wash process because a ready market can be found for
gypsum, a byproduct. The utilities and the building industry began talks
promptly when it became clear what volume of gypsum would be produced and
effective disposal arrangements have evolved.
In some cases, the building materials industry has set up shop close to the
power stations. For example, Rigips built a new plasterboard factory at
Gelsenkirchen-Buer within an easy pumping distance of three Veba Kraftwerk
Ruhr (VKR) power stations. These now supply 250,000 tonnes a year of gypsum
in water suspension through pipes to the Rigips factory, accounting for half
of VKR total gypsum production from its power station capacity.
In other cases, the fact that power stations operate at highest load in
winter but the building industry is in full swing in summer means the gypsum
must be stored before being transported during the warmer months to
different parts of Germany.
Fortunately, the German gypsum market has a volume of about 4m tonnes while
'hard coal' power stations produce 2.5m-2.8m tonnes a year.
The sale price achieved for the FGD gypsum generally covers only the cost of
storage and transport, making no contribution to the costs of operating the
FGD plant.
The story for gypsum produced from brown coal power station FGD plant is
rather different.
Partly due to the much higher sulphur level in brown coal, the gypsum
byproduct is yellow in colour and not of optimum quality. As a result, brown
coal power station operator RWE Energie has trouble marketing the gypsum.
But because the huge holes left by open-cast brown coal mining have to be
filled, disposal of the brown coal FGD-produced gypsum has not proved too
much of a problem.
When the German desulphurisation programme began, there was some criticism
that although the benefits to the environment were clearly very great, the
huge investment involved would prolong the life of generally inefficient
power stations.
In particular, brown coal power stations in western Germany have an
efficiency of just 34-38 per cent, so that more than 60 per cent of the fuel
input is lost as heat through the cooling towers. The FGD plant itself also
reduces both hard and brown coal power station efficiency by about 1 per
cent through the power consumption necessary for its operation.
Regardless of such criticism, FGD has now become state-of-the-art power
station technology in Germany. In fact, last year, leading utility
Preussenelektra decided not to use the new coal gasification technology for
a 400MW hard coal power station to be built at Luebeck, which would have
done away with the need for an FGD plant. It decided to use conventional
technology with FGD instead, concluding that efficiency and emissions would
be comparable.
A 900MW hard coal power station planned for Stendal at the beginning of the
next century by east German utility Veag is also on the drawing board as a
further-improved conventional hard coal-fired plant with FGD.
In eastern Germany, several new 800MW brown coal units with FGD are under
construction or planned.
The author is a regular contributor to the Financial Times Newsletter Power
in Europe.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
