<PROFILE>_AN-EANDNAC3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Survey of Drax - The Big Clean-up (5): Complex structure of
controls - Environmental pressures in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Drax's flue gas desulphurisation plant, while much the most ambitious in
Europe, is something of a late-comer in the context of moves to curb air
pollution in the region.
Over the past 20 years, a complex structure of emission controls has evolved
at both supra-national and national levels. These have been successful in
bringing about marked reductions in emissions in countries such as Germany,
for example, where fears of acid rain were strongest.
In other countries, such as the UK, progress has been slower because
governments have been sensitive to the enormous costs of power station
clean-up, particularly when it entails 'end of pipe' solutions. The quest
for alternative means of reducing pollution has also intensified.
Serious attempts to clean up the atmosphere at an international level began
in the 1970s when fears of the threat posed by acid rain prompted
negotiations in the UN's Economic Commission for Europe in Geneva.
This led to the 1985 Sulphur Protocol which committed signatories to reduce
emissions of sulphur dioxide to 70 per cent of 1980 levels by 1993. In 1988,
a similar protocol committed signatories to cut nitrous oxide emissions by
30 per cent by 1995-98.
In 1988, the European Union adopted the Large Combustion Plants Directive
which aimed to take the protocol a stage further. This called for reductions
of sulphur dioxide from existing plants of 25, 43 and 70 per cent by 1993,
1995 and 2003 respectively from 1980 levels. But it gave special
dispensation to countries with heavily reliance on large coal-fired power
stations, with targets of 20, 40 and 60 per cent respectively. The directive
also set a timetable for cuts in nitrous oxide.
The other aim of the directive was to set tough emission limits for new
plants - limits which are now in force.
These measures, plus others taken at the national level, have already
produced sharp reductions in emissions. Germany, with characteristic
thoroughness, has gone furthest. Following a 1983 ordinance, it has attached
clean-up equipment to all plants in the former West Germany. This has led to
cuts of 90 per cent in sulphur emissions, and 75 per cent in nitrous oxide.
But the cost of this has been huge. The total programme amounted to DM22bn,
plus DM5bn of annual operating costs. This adds about 3 pfennigs to the cost
of a kWh, according to estimates by VDEW, the electricity industry trade
association. Work has now started on the clean up of some 10,000MW of
coal-fired capacity in the former East Germany, with a completion target
date of 1996, again at a cost of billions of DM.
The experience of the first phase of clean-up is now having its effect as
European countries address the next stage.
Now that the first set of target dates for the sulphur protocol reductions
has been reached, moves are afoot to tighten the rules still further. Last
year, negotiations began on a second sulphur protocol which aims to bring
about further reductions by the year 2000.
The EU will also be updating the Large Combustion Plants Directive this
year, but although there is some concern in the power generation industry
that this might lead to even tighter targets, officials say that the new
LCPD is likely to fit in with the new protocol.
Unlike the first protocol, the second does not aim for blanket reductions in
emissions. The hope is to get a more flexible system which takes account of
the localities where environmental damage is being caused, and the ability
of those localities to cope with the pollution - an approach known as
critical load analysis which is supposed to give a clearer idea of where the
priorities lie.
Some countries, for example, are being asked to cut sulphur by 90 per cent,
others by only 50 per cent, although environmentalists complain that even
this is not sufficient because the effects of acid deposition are
cumulative, and even small amounts make a difference.
The new protocol is also likely to permit greater flexibility as to how the
results are actually achieved so as to bring a degree of cost effectiveness
into the equation. Although the principle of Best Available Techniques Not
Entailing Excessive Cost (BATNEEC) is the traditional method, some
signatories, such as the UK, want the protocol to leave room for alternative
means.
This has produced a debate about the merits of different pollution reduction
methods. One of these is economic instruments, including tradeable pollution
permits which have been launched in the US but have yet to make an
appearance in Europe, although countries such as the UK have been studying
them closely.
Another method is to encourage use of cleaner energy sources. France, with
its strong development of nuclear power, has achieved most by this means:
its power stations emissions are among the lowest in Europe on a per capita
basis.
Britain also hopes to make a lot of headway towards its targets by switching
from coal to gas - a process which is already well under way although at
considerable political cost, given last year's uproar over closures of
coalmines.
But this is a route down which Germany is clearly not prepared to go: it has
been unable to agree a shift from coal to nuclear power, and has no other
viable fuels to fall back on. It will therefore have to take the costliest
route of pursuing its retrofit programme. Even so, the EU Commission expects
the consumption of gas by Europe's power stations to increase sixfold by the
year 2020.
However, there are also other means, such as introducing greater energy
efficiency, or new clean technology for burning coal.
The efficiency option has recently been undermined by the fall in oil
prices, and by the failure of EU countries to agree some kind of energy tax,
such as a carbon tax, which might push the cost of electricity up to levels
which encourage greater savings. However the proposal has the support of a
number of EU members and is likely to remain on the negotiating table.
Individual countries are also jacking up fuel taxes, which is having the
same effect.
