<PROFILE>_AN-EANDNAC0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Survey of Drax - The Big Clean-up (2): Celebrations after a
difficult year - The Contractors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last month, Babcock Energy formally handed over to National Power the first
two of six sulphur dioxide absorber towers and associated plant which it is
building at the Drax power station on an eight-year Pounds 400m-plus
contract.
After a difficult year at Drax for the subsidiary of Babcock International,
it was a time for celebration - tinged with feelings of relief.
According to Dr John Parker, chief executive and deputy chairman of the
engineering contractor, the completion of the first phase of the project was
'a major technological and operational achievement for both Babcock and
National Power and is the culmination of five years work on the contract to
ensure completion on time and to specification.'
Work on the remaining four units was proceeding to plan, said Babcock, and
more than 75 per cent of the contract had been carried out. The final pair
of absorbers would be handed over to National Power on the scheduled
contract dates in the spring of 1996.
The handover in December came only three months after Babcock had revealed
that it would be taking a Pounds 15m pre-tax provision to cover
higher-than-expected costs on the contract - along with a further Pounds 5m
provision to cover costs of closing non-core mining activities in Africa.
The news shocked the City of London, caused a 20 per cent overnight fall in
Babcock's share price and once again underlined the risks inherent in
large-scale engineering contracts.
Babcock's problems at Drax have, perhaps inevitably, overshadowed its
achievements on the contract and those of other suppliers and contractors.
The scale of the project, with 85km of pipework, 29,000 tons of steelwork,
and large ductwork assemblies which were moved around on the equivalent of
roller skates before being lifted into position, has produced some
significant construction achievements.
Building the FGD plant required the sinking of 14,000 piles into ground
close to the operating plant. For, apart from some temporary interruptions,
Drax has been continuing to produce power - which has been very important to
the customer.
'The ability of the construction team to build the FGD plant while reducing
the impact on our biggest revenue-earner has been masterful,' says Mr
Granville Camsey, National Power's executive director with overall
responsibility for the Drax project.
Overall, the project is running on time and under budget. The original
estimate was Pounds 750m, Mr Camsey says, but the eventual total cost will
be about Pounds 680m.
Apart from Babcock Energy, National Power has had about 50 main contractors
on site. Of them, the largest amount of work went to Birtley Engineering,
which won Pounds 30m of contracts to supply the materials handling system
and a waste water treatment plant. It is followed by Mowlem Civil
Engineering, which did Pounds 19.5m of piling, unit plant and ductwork
foundations, Amec Civil Engineering (Pounds 19m of work on common plant
foundations), Alfred McAlpine (Pounds 12m of preliminary civil works), and
W. S. Atkins (a Pounds 9m civil design consultancy contract).
Babcock Energy itself has also given work worth more than Pounds 1m apiece
to more than than 30 sub-contractors. By far the biggest contract, worth
about Pounds 45m, went to Cleveland Structural Engineering for all the
structural steelwork and cladding. Howden Sirocco won a Pounds 22m contract
for gas heaters and booster fans, while contracts of about Pounds 15m each
went to Plastilon of France for the glass reinforced plastic (GRP) pipework,
Balfour Kilpatrick for cabling and Ancorite for the absorber and flue
linings. Thompson Kennicott, part of Rolls-Royce, provided waste water
treatment plant in a deal worth about Pounds 10m.
Other household names from construction and engineering include M. J.
Gleeson, GEC Alsthom, Weir Pumps and Asea Brown Boveri. ABB had control
system contracts from both Babcock Energy and National Power itself, worth a
total of about Pounds 10m.
Overall, the bulk of the spending on the project has been in the UK -
National Power estimates that only about Pounds 45m of work was supplied
from overseas. At its peak, about 2,300 people were employed on site, but
the overall employment effect for such projects is normally between three
and five times that number - if steelmakers, transporters and others even
remotely involved are included.
For many of the suppliers, and especially Babcock itself, the Drax FGD
project has been one of their first experiences of the way the privatised
utilities are handling very big capital investments. In contrast to the
highly-detailed technical design work which used to be carried out by the
old Central Electricity Generating Board, National Power gave Babcock a
performance specification it must work to but very little technical
definition.
This is a fundamental change, says Mr Camsey, from what contractors and
customers are used to. The relationship between the two is now based around
performance-related criteria. National Power, for example laid down what it
wanted in terms of performance and durability from the project's pipework,
but did not say what it should be made of. In consultation with the
customer, Babcock decided on using GRP for 80 per cent of the pipework
rather than rubber-lined steel. Babcock also decided to line the mild steel
ductwork with a nickel-based material, Hastalloy, to meet performance
criteria there.
This method of construction clearly requires a high degree of trust between
customer and supplier but also needs a mechanism than enables both to spot
problems early and take action accordingly.
Leaving aside the relatively minor problem of a fire at one of Plastilon's
plants, the big problem has been at the heart of the FGD process itself.
The massive steel absorbers have to be lined with rubber to prevent
corrosion, but in August 1992 imperfections in the steel plate were
discovered after shotblasting, says Mr Keith Thorley, Babcock Energy's
project manager at Drax. Consequently, reaching the required level of
smoothness and cleanliness for the linings to stick properly proved to be
much more difficult than had first been thought.
Part of the problem was the specification of the steel plate itself, says Mr
William Fairney, National Power's director of project development and
construction. The original plate was supplied from the UK, but Babcock says
that for the later units it is switching to steel from a Belgium supplier
which was able to give guarantees on imperfection-free plate.
The technical problem in the absorbers was solved by Christmas 1992, but 20
weeks had been lost. National Power could see that Babcock would not be able
to complete the first two absorbers by December 1993 without considerable
additional manpower to catch up with its schedule.
'We sat down with them to look at the problem,' says Mr Camsey. 'They
realised they had to bring in more people.' This was the origin of Babcock's
cost overrun - which emerged in the summer after an independent team from
Babcock head office found a Pounds 15m gap between expected future revenue
on the contract and predicted costs.
Babcock's management team on site has been strengthened and top-level
oversight of the project tightened up through appointment of a director
dedicated to the project.
Mr Camsey says there has been some tough talking between contractor and
customer, and even some 'blood-letting.' But he adds that, overall 'in a
technical and a project management sense, Babcock have been good, and we are
satisfied.' The handover of the first two absorbers was made a day before
the December 17 deadline.
Mr Fairney adds that Babcock must be given credit for the way it handled
three 12-week outages (utility-speak for stopping production) for the
critical installation of the ductwork into the flues. It finished the first
with two days to spare, the second with seven days, and the third with 11
days to spare.
Both contractor and customer are now confident that the four remaining
absorbers will go ahead without further technical problems after the lessons
learnt on the first pair. The two sides will probably continue discussing
terms until the contract is completed and Babcock said in September it was
in talks with National Power about recovery of 'certain elements' of the
additional costs. Whether it achieves that remains to be seen - Mr Camsey
says 'No comment.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>National Power.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1629 Heavy Construction, NEC.
    P1623 Water, Sewer and Utility Lines.
    P4911 Electric Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
