<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT941-15569</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EANDNACZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Survey of Drax - The Big Clean-up (3): Emerging technologies
 -The Alternatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power, along with other generators of power from coal-fired
stations, has had two broad technology options when deciding how to respond
to the increasing pressure to reduce sulphur dioxide emissions.
The first is to use one of at least four methods to retrofit flue gas
desulphurisation (FGD) equipment to an existing coal-fired plant. These
methods essentially aim to improve the traditional pulverised coal firing
process through various emission controls after combustion.
The second is to start afresh with a new power station and a new method of
combustion. Typically, that would mean switching to combined cycle gas
turbine power generation, a significantly cleaner method than traditional
coal-fired generation. The extreme, no-emission, option is nuclear power.
In between are emerging technologies which use coal. Integrated gasification
combined cycle (IGCC), for example, involves turning coal into a gas which
is then used to fire gas turbines.
Relatively new types of boilers using fluidised bed combustion, which has a
number of variants, involve burning powdered coal in a bed of pulverised
limestone.
In the years up to the placing of the Drax contracts in 1988, the former
Central Electricity Generating Board weighed the various options for
cleaning up the station. Given the size of Drax - six 660MW units - it is
perhaps hardly surprising that the options it considered were the FGD
routes.
This was the prevailing philosophy in the early- to mid-1980s. European and
Japanese utilities were making use of the wide range of FGD choices
available, says Mr Granville Camsey, a National Power executive director and
managing director (group technology).
All the choices, he says, involve GCE 'O-Level' chemistry. The decision on
which technology to use will be based on cost-benefit grounds, and could be
influenced by anything from the chemical content of the coal to the
availability of seawater.
The choice at Drax has emerged as comfortably the most popular of the four
main FGD routes. This is the limestone-gypsum process, used on about half of
the 180 gigawatts of power plant fitted with FGD equipment worldwide.
The process uses the alkaline calcium carbonate in naturally occurring
limestone to capture the sulphur dioxide by contact with the flue gas in a
wet scrubbing vessel.
The byproduct, apart from water, is gypsum (calcium sulphate), the raw
material for plasterboard and other products used in the construction
industry. This consequently gives the process a commercial aspect that is
often lacking in environmental clean-up technology.
The second most popular FGD route is the regenerative process, which also
involves wet scrubbing and has a commercial spin-off. This uses a
sodium-based alkaline scrubbing liquor to capture the SO. The spent liquor
can be treated so that it can be used again, and the separate stream of
SO-rich gas can be sold or turned into sulphur or sulphuric acid, for use by
the chemical industry.
The two other main FGD processes are seawater washing, which uses the
natural alkalinity of seawater to remove the SO from the flue gas in a wet
scrubbing vessel. Air and fresh seawater are added to the scrubbing liquor
to neutralise pH levels before it is returned to the sea.
There are snags, however. There are no commercial byproducts; huge amounts
of seawater are required; and the flue gas has to be reheated for the
process to work, which is costly, leaving large quantities of warm seawater
to be returned whence it came.
In the fourth process, spray drying, powdered lime is injected into a dry
scrubbing vessel and the SO is removed by contact with humidified flue gas.
A solid by-product, a mixture of calcium sulphite-sulphate-carbonate and
flyash, can be partly re-used in the process but has no commercial use.
Spray-drying is not really an option for a large baseload plant such as Drax
because it it only captures about 50 per cent of the flue gas, compared with
as much as 90 per cent for the limestone-gypsum process, says Mr Camsey. It
would be more suitable for a power station used only for peak loads.
As it happens, there is a similar reason for preferring the limestone-gypsum
process than taking an entirely different tack, which is to use low-sulphur
coals instead of FGD. These coals, available on the international market,
typically have a sulphur content of about 0.8 per cent, about half that of
UK coals, so their use would only halve SO emissions. Low-sulphur coals can
be used with FGD, although that would reduce the amount of gypsum
by-product.
Since the old CEGB decided on its FGD route for Drax, priorities have
changed for utilities such as National Power, all of which have a
responsibility to reduce emissions. The question now is less likely to be
'Which FGD route should we use?' than 'Is it commercially more viable to use
FGD or start afresh?'
The 'dash for gas' - in the UK and elsewhere - is evidence of how this
question is being answered. Widespread acceptance of gas as a fuel for power
generation is relatively recent, but its use in combined cycle power
generation produces electricity more efficiently and more cleanly than
large-scale coal-burning.
As for clean coal technologies, the focus has switched from FGD with its
high installation costs to processes which are promising for greenfield
sites but cannot economically be retrofitted.
The big power equipment suppliers are spending heavily on two main methods
of fluidised bed combustion: pressurised FBC and circulating FBC. The latter
has so far won greater commercial acceptance but PFBC is coming up from
behind with strong backing from Asea Brown Boveri, the Swiss-Swedish group.
Mr Camsey's preferred clean coal choice, however, is IGCC. National Power is
participating in a European Union-backed project to build a 350MW IGCC plant
in Spain, due to be commissioned in 1997. Another IGCC demonstration plant,
designed by Shell and located at Buggenum in the Netherlands, is now being
commissioned.
Unlike the modern boiler technologies, which are dependent on coal, IGCC
could offer flexibility of fuel use between coal and gas, says Mr Camsey. As
the costs of IGCC equipment come down and if gas prices rise relative to
coal, it could be retrofitted onto a combined cycle plant.
</TEXT>
