<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Generator re-ignites row over coal policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power, the electricity generator, yesterday re-ignited the
controversy over coal policy. It said the cost of producing power from
combined-cycle gas stations was nearly 30 per cent higher per unit than from
coal-fired plants which they are replacing.
The company's breakdown of costs, which it had kept confidential until
yesterday, will provide ammunition for the coal lobby as it prepares to
fight a new round of expected pit closures.
Coal industry supporters have argued that distortions in the market rather
than the economics of producing power from different sources are responsible
for the contraction of the coal industry and the so-called dash for gas.
Separately, the government's pollution inspectorate indicated that it
expected PowerGen, the other large generator in England and Wales, to
proceed with fitting 2,000MW of flue-gas desulphurisation equipment in
addition to the 2,000MW it is already building.
In its flotation document three years ago PowerGen indicated plans for
building 4,000MW of FGD equipment. The coal lobby regards this as a
commitment but PowerGen has held back from ordering the second 2,000MW. The
inspectorate said it looked forward to the 'satisfactory completion' of
8,000MW in the generators' gas desulphurisation programme. This implies an
expectation that PowerGen would complete 4,000MW.
The inspectorate's statement came as National Power marked the opening of
the first phase of its 4,000MW FGD project at its Drax station in North
Yorkshire. Mr Roger Witcomb, National Power's UK director of business
planning, said the cost of electricity from combined-cycle gas turbines
running flat out was about 2.7p per kilowatt hour, compared with 2.1p from
older plants they are replacing. The 0.6p difference was the same as the
cost of fitting and running FGDs at Drax.
The coal lobby will see the figures as strengthening their argument that the
UK should invest more in FGDs rather than retire coal-generation plants
early.
Drax Survey, Pages 11-15
</TEXT>
