<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Temporary reprieve for Elstree Studios
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Elstree studios, birthplace of successful cinema and television productions
such as Capital City, has won a temporary reprieve from demolition.
Yesterday the High Court ruled that Hertsmere borough council had an
arguable case for insisting that the owner, Brent Walker, keep the site
open.
The Hertfordshire studios, where Laurence Olivier made his screen debut, was
used to make blockbusters such as Chitty Chitty Bang Bang, Star Wars,
Superman, and the Indiana Jones adventures.
Brent Walker has given an undertaking not to proceed with demolition,
pending a full hearing of the council's case. The company has outline
planning permission to develop half the site as a retail superstore. Last
year it announced that the studios complex on the other half would close
because it was under-used.
But the council says it was a planning condition that the area would be kept
for film and TV production until 2015.
