<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / BAe plans another 580 job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace plans to cut a further 580 jobs in its Avro regional jet
activities at Woodford, near Manchester, to reduce costs and improve
competitiveness after the setback in its partnership negotiations with
Taiwan.
The cuts will reduce the company's regional jet workforce of about 3,000 by
nearly 20 per cent.
At the peak three years ago there were about 8,000 workers at Woodford and
Hatfield, Hertfordshire. BAe has since shut down Hatfield and concentrated
regional jet activities - which involve the production of RJ Avroliners and
BAe 146s - at Woodford.
The company said this had led to savings of about 30 per cent, but it is now
seeking to cut costs further after difficulties in negotiating a regional
jet joint-venture agreement with Taiwan Aerospace.
Talks have now been suspended, although BAe yesterday said it was
maintaining a dialogue. The company has held talks with other manufacturers
over possible collaboration in the regional jet sector, which is suffering
from overcapacity in a depressed market.
BAe made a Pounds 750m after-tax provision in its 1992 accounts to cover its
loss-making regional jet activities. For the past 12 months it has tried to
reach a joint-venture agreement with Taiwan to secure the future of its
regional jet operations.
The company told unions before Christmas that in spite of the suspension of
talks it intended to pursue its regional jet activities on its own as a
result of the productivity gains and cost savings from concentration of
production.
But the latest job cuts suggests the company is having to intensify its
drive to cut costs in the face of continuing pressures.
The Avro regional jet activities delivered 17 aircraft last year compared
with a peak production of about 40 three years ago. It also won orders for
11 aircraft last year.
</TEXT>
