<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Adams is 'open to persuasion'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, is 'very open to being persuaded' that
the Downing Street declaration provides a basis for an end to the IRA's
military campaign, he said yesterday.
But in a long statement he insisted that there was a need for clarifications
of the declaration and for 'immediate and unconditional dialogue with both
governments'.
He said Sinn Fein would respond positively to efforts to close a perceived
gap between the Hume-Adams peace initiative - which was launched last
September by Mr Adams and Mr John Hume, leader of the Social Democratic and
Labour party - and the Downing Street declaration. But he accused the
British government of being 'belligerent, arrogant and provocative' in
statements subsequent to the declaration last December.
'I am quite confident that the IRA would respond positively to a package
containing the principles, process and dynamic (of the Hume-Adams
initiative) . . . up to now I do not have any political package with which
to approach the IRA,' he said.
Mr Adams said that key issues in Sinn Fein's strategy were that the British
government should end partition 'and hand over sovereignty to an all-Ireland
government', that the British government should 'influence unionist
attitudes' in this direction, and that the London and Dublin governments
'should consult together to seek agreement on the policy objective of ending
partition'.
He said a viable peace process was 'dependent on the adoption of the
(Hume-Adams) proposals by the two governments'. Mr Hume has already welcomed
the Downing Street declaration.
Mr Adams lays great emphasis on the British government becoming 'persuaders'
of the unionist community in Northern Ireland to accept an all-Ireland
solution, a point which has been emphatically ruled out by the UK
government.
The Irish government insists that many of Sinn Fein's concerns have been
addressed by the joint declaration, and has attempted to persuade the party
to accept it by offering further clarifications, lifting a 20-year
broadcasting ban on Sinn Fein, and an immediate seat at a new 'peace forum'
in the republic if the IRA ended its military campaign.
</TEXT>
