<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Trust hospitals to publish chiefs' pay under ethics code
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Codes designed to strengthen ethical standards and accountability in the
National Health Service were published yesterday in the wake of serious
criticisms of mismanagement and financial waste.
Boards running hospitals and health authorities will be required to declare
members' private interests and income from NHS sources. This will mean
publishing salary details of chief executives and other executive directors
of trust hospitals, which previously did not have to be disclosed.
The NHS's reputation for probity has been seriously dented by recent reports
from the Commons public accounts committee on mismanagement in the West
Midlands and Wessex regions. These concluded that at least Pounds 20m had
been wasted in Wessex and Pounds 10m in the West Midlands, and spoke of
evidence of conflicts of interest, concealment of information and
shortcomings in managerial and financial control.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, said yesterday that criticisms
from the public accounts committee and the Audit Commission were justified.
All corporate and personal conduct in the NHS must be underpinned by
accountability, probity and openness, and the new codes set out corporate
standards that the public could expect to apply.
The codes, drawn up by a working group established last year, will be
introduced in April. Consultation on their final form will take place until
February 18, but the main elements will include defining more clearly the
functions of chairmen and non-executive members of NHS boards; require
boards to establish audit and remuneration committees, and record all board
members' private interests relevant to NHS business.
Accounting, tendering and employment practices, said Mrs Bottomley, must
reflect the highest personal standards. 'Chairmen and board members should
act impartially and should not be influenced by social or business
relationships. No one should use their public position to further their
private interests.'
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said the proposals would do
little to raise NHS standards of accountability and did 'not begin to
address the real concerns raised by the scandals in Wessex and the West
Midlands'.
The codes emphasise that it is unacceptable for any NHS board or individual
to 'ignore public service values in achieving results'.
Some trust hospitals have been criticised for paying senior executives
salaries that are high by public-sector standards, or not disclosing
remuneration details. Mrs Bottomley said she did not think it appropriate
for her to set pay ceilings throughout the service. There might be local
circumstances where it was appropriate to pay an above-average salary.
The government hopes, however, that the requirement to publish details will
eliminate any potential for abuse.
</TEXT>
