<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Milk market left in disarray by delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Pounds 3bn milk market in England and Wales has been thrown into
disarray by the government's decision earlier this week to delay plans to
open it up to competition. Mrs Gillian Shephard, agriculture minister,
rejected a plan for reorganising the Milk Marketing Board into a producer's
co-operative in time for the board to be abolished by April 1.
The market liberalisation could now be put off until the beginning of July
or even October, with the board remaining the statutory buyer and seller of
milk until then.
Some dairies have threatened to by-pass the board from April, even though it
would be technically illegal. 'My fear is that a Sunday trading situation
will develop if a lot of companies break the law,' said Mr Richard Smith,
who heads the Northern Milk Partnership.
The uncertainty has cast a shadow over some investment plans. 'While there
is this insecurity in the market, it is difficult to commit money to capital
investment,' said Mr Roger Clarke, commercial director at MD Foods, which is
holding back investment of up to Pounds 12m until the situation is clearer.
The Milk Marketing Board has to address important issues such as its plans
for selling milk in the new competitive environment, transfer of assets to
the new co-operative and haulage arrangements before it can gain approval
from government.
The Ministry of Agriculture is then expected to put the board's plans to
another consultation period which could take three months.
The milk marketing year begins in April, when farmers make their financial
plans for the coming season. The abolition of the board part way through the
year makes it difficult to plan ahead.
In addition, the board generally pays farmers a premium of up to 3p per
litre for milk during the summer in an effort to encourage production in a
slack period.
Farmers fear the board will abandon the practice this year in order to
preserve its cashflow before abolition.
Board officials, in an attempt to reassure farmers, stress it is just a
delay they face rather than any fundamental changes to the new market.
</TEXT>
