FT  14 JAN 94 / Smaller civil service forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The top civil servant in the Office of Public Service and Science yesterday
predicted a 'generally smaller' government and civil service in the
mid-1990s with its functions limited to the essentials.
Mr Richard Mottram, permanent secretary at the Cabinet Office responsible
for carrying out the government's public-service reform initiatives, said
government would concentrate on a few core functions over the next few years
 -resource allocation, strategic and policy issues, procurement of services,
and essential finance and personnel work.
He acknowledged this amounted to a 'very large challenge in raising quality
and reducing costs' - but defended progress to date in putting out to tender
Pounds 1.5bn of work done by departments.
Mr Mottram, addressing the Royal United Services Institute, said about
Pounds 1bn of work had been hived off since last November - either
contracted out or entrusted to executive agencies - with a further Pounds
800m due to be allocated in the current year.
On the defence sector, Mr Mottram - who previously served in the Ministry of
Defence - said there was still scope for reform.
