<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Tax change hits property schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday announced a change to its tax legislation which
will affect the ability of some property owners, such as London's Canary
Wharf, to take advantage of tax breaks in enterprise zones.
The rule change could have a severe impact on the viability of enterprise
zone trusts, which are tax-based property investment schemes for private
investors, said investment adviser Mr John Spiers of BESt Investment. Some
property developers in enterprise zones would regard the change as a 'a
breach of faith', he said.
Mr Stephen Dorrell, the financial secretary to the Treasury, said the
government was rectifying a weakness in its capital allowances legislation,
by which property owners have been able to retain the benefit of their tax
allowances when they sold a long lease in the building.
The announcement could seriously delay Canary Wharf's ability to take
advantage of several hundred millions of pounds of capital allowances.
Yesterday it cancelled plans to launch an enterprise zone trust, as a result
of the announcement.
Mr Patrick Garner, finance director of Canary Wharf, said that the change
'in no way affects the viability of Canary Wharf'. Shareholders had not
factored in the benefits of the capital allowances into their calculations
in making their decision to take the scheme out of administration, he said.
The new rules will make it more difficult for some property owners to take
advantage of tax breaks by selling parts of their buildings to investors.
</TEXT>
