<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Manpower signs deal over strikes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unison, Britain's largest union, has signed a no-strikebreaking agreement
with Manpower, the employment agency.
Manpower, which placed 66,000 people in temporary employment last year, said
it had agreed not to support strike breakers or to allow agency staff to
cross picket lines.
In return, the union has agreed not to obstruct commercial opportunities
open to Manpower. In effect, the deal is something of an employment peace
treaty designed to keep the agency and the union on friendly terms.
Manpower said it would not encourage its employees to join the union but
agreed that it would issue union enrolment forms at the time of interviews
and 'point out the benefits of union membership'.
Manpower said: 'We offer them the opportunity to join a union appropriate to
the work they are doing.
'It is entirely their choice but we draw people's attention to it.'
The company said that as a matter of policy it did not allow itself to be
used for strike-breaking.
The union signed a similar agreement with the Reed Care employment agency in
June which covered care assist-ants.
Mr Keith Sonnet, assistant general secretary, said: 'The agreement widens
our influence over the treatment of temporary staff and will enable us to
look after their conditions of work more closely.
'It guarantees temporary staff will not be used where industrial action is
taking place or be substituted for permanent staff.'
</TEXT>
