<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / The Westminster Report: MPs see threat to Major's position
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shocked Conservative MPs were last night absorbing the details of the report
into Westminster council which some think threatens the leadership of Mr
John Major, the prime minister.
Most repeated warnings by Mr Major and other cabinet ministers that MPs
should not 'rush to judgment' on the provisional findings released by the
district auditor.
A few also sought to minimise the impact of the report by drawing attention
to auditors' investigations into the financial problems of the
Labour-controlled councils of Monklands in Strathclyde, Liverpool, and
Lambeth, south London.
Mr Bernard Jenkin (Colchester North) said that Westminster council was 'one
of the best housing authorities in London'. He told laughing Labour MPs: 'It
is not a crime to encourage home ownership.'
But there was mounting gloom in the Conservative ranks as MPs thumbed
through unofficial copies of the unpublished full version of the district
auditor's report.
Labour MPs said the full report contained even stronger criticism of
Westminster Conservatives than had been expected.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, gleefully drew attention to
repeated previous endorsements by cabinet ministers of Westminster as a
Conservative flagship council.
He said the report showed that the Conservative party had abandoned basic
principles of public morality by putting party interests before the public
good. The Conservatives had ignored the laws and conventions which separated
functioning democracies from banana republics.
Mr Straw added: 'Arrogance, incompetence and utter contempt for those who
disagree with them have led to the systematic disregard of those laws and
conventions by the Tory party.
'The public interest, and the Tory party's internal interest have, in the
minds of leading Conservatives, become indistinguishable. The public's
government has become the Tory party's private fiefdom.'
The allegations against Westminster councillors dominated Mr Major's first
appearance at question time since the Commons resumed after the Christmas
recess.
Amid rowdy scenes, Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, labelled the report 'a
devastating example of financial corruption and the abuse of power by senior
members of the Conservative party'.
Mr Major retorted: 'If the allegations are confirmed, I condemn it
unreservedly. But as has been made clear, this is the start of the legal
process.
'Unlike you, most people will prefer to wait until that is completed and not
to find people guilty until and unless they are proven to be guilty.'
Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, also urged MPs to reserve judgment
until the auditor's final report was completed.
However, he added: 'If these allegations turn out to be supported and
proved, no one will be tougher in opposition to them or in my insistence
that the law should take its course.'
</TEXT>
