<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / The Westminster Report: Party chiefs heaped praise on
'flagship'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A history of praising Westminster city council makes it almost impossible
for the national Conservative party to distance itself now.
Westminster, which has always been Conservative-controlled, emerged as a
Tory 'flagship' in the late 1980s.
In 1990, the year the community charge or poll tax was introduced,
Westminster and neighbouring Wandsworth were promoted by Mr Kenneth Baker,
then Conservative party chairman, as 'flagship boroughs'. Results from the
two boroughs dominated the headlines the day after the local elections that
year, where elsewhere in the country Conservatives made serious losses.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's local government spokesman, yesterday relished
publishing details of previous praise heaped on Westminster by ministers
during the campaign.
In 1990 Mr David Hunt - now the employment secretary but then minister with
responsibility for the community charge - described Westminster's election
performance as a 'stunning success' and 'a source of cheer for every
Conservative'.
Mr Baker, in his memoirs, describes the council as being led 'with verve by
Shirley Porter . . . with spirit and imagination she had cut back
expenditure but improved services'.
Westminster's role as a 'pioneer' for ambitious Conservative policies has
continued. Its council tax is one of the lowest in the country and is
proudly displayed on a banner in City Hall. It has also introduced a series
of controversial reforms. These have not been thwarted by the district
auditor's investigations.
Only last month Westminster became the first council to invite the private
sector to take over its day nurseries. The council is in the forefront of
extending competitive tendering beyond manual blue-collar services.
It also took a more confrontational stance in last year's dispute between
the government and the teachings unions over national curriculum testing.
Westminster sent a letter to headteachers threatening that those who refused
to co-operate in carrying out national curriculum testing 'should have
deductions made from their salary'.
It also said that deductions from teachers' pay would be made. The move was
widely interpreted as an attempt by the government to persuade other
education authorities to take a similar stance, although eventually the
tests were boycotted in all Westminster schools, and the council took no
action.
Dame Shirley Porter was the figurehead of the flagship. Leader for eight
years until 1991 and then mayor of Westminster for a year, she was arguably
the best-known Tory politician in the capital.
However, she was no stranger to financial controversy, the most famous
incident being the decision by the council in 1986 to sell three cemeteries
for a total of 15p. In 1990 the district auditor found no case for
surcharging councillors over the cemeteries, which had been valued at more
than Pounds 15m, but the decision opened the council to ridicule before the
1990 elections.
The council rode out that storm, but the repercussions of the
'gerrymandering' allegations could last much longer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
