<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / The Westminister Report: Legg refutes allegations of
impropriety
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Barry Legg, the Conservative MP for Milton Keynes South-West, was chief
Tory whip during his 12-year spell as a Westminster councillor and thus
played an important role in formulating council policy, David Owen and Peter
Marsh write.
Mr Legg said yesterday: 'I utterly refute any suggestion of impropriety.
When the time comes for me to put my case I will be answering in full the
matters raised in the report.'
Mr Derrick Conner, treasurer of the Bletchley Conservative Club, which lies
in Mr Legg's constituency, said: 'I can't pick any holes in his performance
as an MP. As far as I am concerned he is innocent until proved guilty.'
Since being elected to parliament in April 1992 for the new constituency of
Milton Keynes South-West, he has made his mark as an astute member of the
Treasury and civil service select committee and as a Maastricht rebel.
A co-founder of the Thatcherite Conservative Way Forward, he was among the
hard core of Tory backbenchers who most uncompromisingly opposed the
Maastricht bill's passage in the Commons last year. This stance will have
won him few friends in the Conservative Whips' Office.
Mr Legg, an accountant, is a former director of the food group Hillsdown
Holdings, remaining as a consultant until last year. He received a Pounds
200,000 severance payment when he left the board after becoming an MP.
Labour - which lost out last time by nearly 4,700 votes - would be
disappointed not to take his seat even in a general election. If a
by-election were to result from the shadow which yesterday's report has cast
over Mr Legg's political career, it would expect to win with a large
majority.
He first ran for parliament in 1983 when he challenged Mr Derek Foster, now
Labour chief whip, for the safe Labour seat of Bishop Auckland, losing by
4,300 votes. Mr Foster remembers him as a 'fairly conventional Tory
opponent'.
Last summer Mr Legg co-authored a radical pamphlet recommending ways of
cutting Pounds 8bn from the social security budget. Ideas included raising
the retirement age to 67 and integrating non-contributory benefits into a
new 'whole-person' benefit.
</TEXT>
