<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Venezuela takes action over bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Venezuela's financial authorities yesterday decided to suspend Banco Latino,
Venezuela's second largest commercial bank in terms of assets, from the
national bank clearing system, said Mr Jose Bouza, president of the
Venezuelan Banking Council.
Banco Latino's cheques will thus not be accepted for clearing as of today,
although Mr Bouza said no decision had been made on government intervention
in the bank.
Banco Latino, whose shares trade on the Caracas Stock Exchange, is the
centrepiece of a group that includes other large financial and leasing
institutions. Mr Bouza said the bank had been the victim of reports of
financial difficulties which had prompted depositors to withdraw large
amounts.
Venezuela's economy suffered a 1 per cent contraction in GDP last year and
there is concern that the recession will have a big impact on weaker
commercial banks.
