<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / World Trade News: US puts weight behind Third World labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Children in Thailand who labour in back-alleys assembling goods, or who sell
themselves as prostitutes, might be reassured to know that the US government
has taken up labour rights cases such as theirs.
US officials say that threats made by the US Trade Representative to
eliminate duty-free status on Thai goods, and on imports from other
developing countries, under the US Generalised System of Preferences GSP,
have produced 'concrete actions' on labour conditions throughout the Third
World.
In a recent report, Mr Mickey Kantor, trade representative, noted with
satisfaction that the Thai government has approved draft legislation which
brings worker rights 'closer to international norms'.
Final enactment is expected before the next session of the Thai parliament
ends in late July. Meanwhile, Mr Kantor's office will be monitoring
progress.
It is also watching in Malawi, Guatemala, El Salvador, Indonesia and other
countries where labour organisers are often jailed or murdered, where the
growth of unions is curbed, where workers are exploited and ill-treated, and
where conditions are unnecessarily hazardous.
For the past decade, US law has required the trade representative to use GSP
benefits to press for improvement in workers' rights in developing
countries. The law was passed despite objections in the 1980s of the Reagan
administration, which never seriously attempted to implement it unless
unfriendly governments were the accused.
The Bush administration improved enforcement, fearing a loss of flexibility
when the GSP came up for congressional renewal. But it investigated labour
petitions with nothing like the enthusiasm it displayed in pursuing
violators of intellectual property rights.
Activity has quickened with the arrival of Mr Kantor as trade representative
under the Clinton administration which began a year ago. He began his law
career helping migrant farm workers. Cases filed at the trade agency by
labour and human rights groups are now seriously investigated and programmes
have been set up to prod various governments.
In its most recent review, the representative's office closed cases against
Costa Rica and Paraguay, these having enacted labour rights legislation. It
commended Malawi's release of a labour leader, Mr Chakufwa Chihana, from
prison and noted that free union elections are scheduled there for early
this year.
'We are terminating the review on the basis of these actions, with the
expectation that union elections will be free and fair and conducted on
schedule,' Mr Kantor said, adding a warning that any reversal of this trend
would lead the US to reopen the case.
The representative gave Guatemala six months to continue progress in
training and hiring labour inspectors, and in reducing the backlog of unions
applying for formal recognition. Oman, too, was given a further six months
to show progress, after it had agreed to joint the International Labour
Organisation and begun to revise its labour laws.
Mr Kantor said a case against El Salvador could be dropped soon if, as
expected, it passes revised labour legislation before the end of the current
legislative session in March.
Although trade officials complain they are not being given sufficient
credit, human rights and labour activists say Mr Kantor still allows foreign
policy considerations to play a role in his office's findings.
'In countries like Mexico, facts fly out the window,' says Mr Pharis Harvey,
executive director of the International Labour Rights Education and Research
Fund.
However, he added, labour groups are at least getting the same 'respect'
from trade officials as business representatives. 'We are no longer seen as
something akin to plague of locusts.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>THZ  Thailand, Asia.
    QQZ  Developing Countries.
</CN>
<XX>
