<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / World Trade News: EU turns screw in banana row - Latin
Americans divided over what Brussels says is its 'last' offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Latin American banana exporters meeting in Costa Rica were yesterday divided
over whether to bow to intense European Union pressure to accept Europe's
proposed new banana import regime.
Acceptance would end a two-and-a-half year row that has sullied relations
between Latin America and Europe. The row has also embarrassed the EU by
exposing its preferential trading arrangements with former colonies as
illegal under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
It would offer several Latin American exporters improved quotas in Europe's
protected banana market, but would legitimise a quota-based regime at a time
when the Uruguay Round agreement on global trade liberalisation, finalised a
month ago, has demanded all quotas be converted to tariffs as a first step
to elimination of protection.
The issue has come to a head this weekend because of the imminent release of
a Gatt panel report on a complaint from five Latin American countries
attacking Europe's banana regime as illegal.
A hard-hitting first panel report, released in July last year, upheld the
Latin American complaints and ruled that the Lome convention of preferential
trading arrangements between EU members and their former colonies could not
be defended as a free trade agreement, or customs union.
In a letter to the trade ministers of Colombia, Costa Rica, Venezuela,
Guatemala and Nicaragua, unprecedentedly signed jointly by three EU
commissioners - Mr Manuel Marn, commissioner for developing countries, Sir
Leon Brittan, trade commissioner, and Mr Rene Steichen, agriculture
commissioner - the Latin Americans were warned that the new quota offer
tabled on December 14 in the final stages of the Uruguay Round negotiation
would not be improved, and would be withdrawn if it was not accepted before
the Gatt panel report is published.
'A decision  .. is now very urgent,' the letter says. 'Once the draft panel
report is sent to the parties involved  .. the offer of December 14 could
not be maintained.'
Main beneficiaries of the new quota offer would be Costa Rica, which would
see its share of the 2.1m tonne quota for 1994 rise to 23.4 per cent from 19
per cent in 1992, Colombia, which would see a 0.8 per cent rise to 22 per
cent over the same period, and Nicaragua, its 1992 share of 1.1 per cent
rising to 1.9 per cent.
The main casualty would be Ecuador, which strategically drove its exports up
to a peak of 27.7 per cent of EU imports in 1992, in the hope of capturing a
larger quota. Its share would be 20.2 per cent.
Of the five Gatt complainants, Guatemala chose to be absent from the meeting
in Costa Rica yesterday and appears reluctant to accept the EU ultimatum.
A Brussels-based Latin American ambassador said yesterday: 'The deal is not
perfect, but it goes a long way to meeting our objectives of better market
access.'
The EC Banana Trade Association condemned the EU ultimatum as limiting
commercial choice, imposing higher costs, and encouraging over-production in
Central America.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XCZ  Latin America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P0179 Fruits and Tree Nuts, NEC.
    P5148 Fresh Fruits and Vegetables.
    P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
