<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / World Trade News: C&amp;W consortium wins Latvian telecom deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Latvian government will today award a contract to modernise the
country's telecommunications network to a consortium headed by Cable &amp;
Wireless, the UK telecommunications group.
The contract includes the privatisation of Lattelekom, the Latvian state
operator. In return for a guaranteed Dollars 160m (Pounds 108.10m) of
investment over the next three years, the consortium will take a 49 per cent
stake in the company.
The deal is the first internationally-tendered privatisation of a state
telecommunications operator in the former Soviet Union. It follows the
partial privatisation of Matav, the Hungarian state operator, last month,
which was the first in the former eastern bloc.
C&amp;W has a 70 per cent stake in the Latvian consortium; Telecom Finland, the
Finnish state-owned operator, the other 30 per cent. The two defeated a bid
by Deutsche Telekom, the German state operator, which won the Matav contract
as head of consortium from which C&amp;W withdrew at a late stage.
C&amp;W and Telecom Finland have agreed to carry through a 10-year modernisation
plan to include the installation of at least 650,000 new digital phone
lines, almost doubling Latvia's number of phone lines.
Although Latvia has one of the former Soviet Union's more extensive phone
networks, its number of lines per head is barely half that in the UK and the
equipment is antiquated. A year ago there was a 170,000-long waiting list
for new lines.
C&amp;W's largest business is Hong Kong Telecom. The Latvian contract
strengthens its north European base. It has an 80 per cent stake in the
second national network in the UK (Mercury), and a 39.9 per cent stake in
the second carrier in Sweden (Tele2).
It also has mobile phone activities in Belarus, and a 40 per cent stake in a
company providing international services in St Petersburg.
Lord Young, C&amp;W chairman, said he expected the Latvian privatisation to set
a precedent for the other Baltic states.
</TEXT>
