</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European Union exporters are optimistic about their chances of forcing
amendments to plans to harmonise insurance regimes governing medium- and
long-term export credit, following a meeting with the European Commission.
But Commission officials warned yesterday that it would be difficult at this
late stage to change the minds of national governments.
Member states' experts have been working on recommendations for
two-and-a-half years, with the aim of eliminating distortions to trade
caused by differences between export credit insurance regimes. The
Commission is poised to absorb their work into a draft proposal, which would
eventually be returned to EU members for formal approval.
A delegation of exporters, led by Mr Keith Johnson, chairman of the British
Exporters' Association, met Commission officials on Wednesday. He said
yesterday that it was 'a very, very positive meeting'.
