<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / World Trade News: Germany to relax dual-use curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARIANE GENILLARD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German cabinet yesterday approved a series of proposals to pave the way
for Germany to comply with European rules on the export of equipment which
could be used for military purposes.
The move illustrates the willingness of the German government to allow
German companies to export dual use industrial goods which can potentially
be used for both civilian and defence purposes.
Germany and Britain have some of the strictest export rules for dual-use
goods in Europe. Germany tightened its legislation three years ago after
German chemical companies were found to have been exporting to goods to
Libya which were used to produce chemical weapons.
German companies have been lobbying to have such strict requirements
relaxed, arguing that they are placing German exporters at a disadvantage.
Members of the ruling Christian Democratic Union (CDU), both in the
parliament and in the government, have increasingly thrown their weight
behind a relaxation of arms exports rules.
The cabinet proposals aim to change the German jurisdiction so it can be
adapted to an EU directive on the export of dual-use goods. The directive,
currently under discussion in Brussels, is expected to follow less stringent
requirements applied by other EU states.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
