<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Strong showing for Old Masters in NY: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first major art sale of 1994, at Christie's in New York on Wednesday,
confirmed that demand for top-quality antiques is becoming steadily
stronger. The auction of Old Master paintings totalled Dollars 15m (Pounds
10m) and was 90 per cent sold by value.
Highest price was the Dollars 2.6m paid for a still life of fruit and
flowers by the Dutch 18th century artist Jan Van Huysum. Its top pre-sale
estimate had been Dollars 1.5m.
One of the last major works by the French artist Louis Boilly, who died in
1845, entitled 'A Carnival on the Boulevard of Crime', sold for Dollars
937,500. It shows low life in the Boulevard de Temple in Paris which had a
reputation for pleasure.
A still life of fruit and marigolds by the 17th century Valencian artist
Tomas Hiepes, estimated at up to Dollars 80,000, sold for Dollars 772,500,
while a typical Roman vista by Panini was at the top of its estimate,
selling for Dollars 640,500.
'We are delighted with the results,' said Rachel Kaminsky, head of
Christie's Old Master department. 'Many lots sold well above their estimates
and the market overall appears to be much stronger than this time last
year'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
