FT  14 JAN 94 / Colombian surrender hits snags
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOGOTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Negotiations on a possible mass surrender by members of the world's biggest
cocaine cartel have hit snags, Colombian government officials said
yesterday, Reuter reports from Bogota.
Lawyers acting for members of the Cali cartel this week reiterated their
bosses' willingness to leave trafficking and surrender, but said they wanted
to serve their sentences under house arrest.
Justice Minister Andres Gonzalez said: 'Policy was set on the subject of
surrendering; it is very clear. People who wish to take advantage of the law
must surrender, must serve their sentences and must serve them in jails.'
