<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Counsel decision takes heat off White House
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton's request for the appointment of a special counsel to
investigate his involvement with the Whitewater property venture and the
bankrupt Madison Guaranty savings and loan entity appeared yesterday to have
drawn some of the sting from the controversy, at least temporarily.
Some of Mr Clinton's Republican foes kept up their attack: Senator Robert
Dole, who only a few days ago was urging Ms Janet Reno, the
attorney-general, to appoint a special counsel, turned around and complained
that her decision to do so, at the White House's request, showed her lack of
independence.
Mr Dole had promised 'no second-guessing' on his part if Ms Reno were to
appoint a special counsel.
Late on Wednesday, though, he changed tack by pressing for a Congressional
select committee to investigate Whitewater - a suggestion seen as having
virtually no chance of approval from the Democratic majority, so long as Ms
Reno's choice of counsel is regarded as acceptable.
Mr Clinton has tersely brushed off questions about Whitewater, which have
distracted attention from his summit meeting with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin this week in Moscow.
Ms Reno declined to comment on the scope of the investigation, saying that
to do so could compromise the independence of the counsel she is to name.
Among the questions that have been raised, however, are those concerning
possible influence by Mr Clinton over thesupervision of Madison, whose
bankruptcy cost the government over Dollars 50m for the reimbursement of
federally insured deposits, and the possible channelling of money from
Madison to Whitewater or to Mr Clinton's campaign funds.
