FT  14 JAN 94 / Tokyo, Moscow talks could be postponed due to changes in
Russian government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese government said talks between Tokyo and Moscow on the
territorial dispute over the northern islands, originally scheduled for this
month, could be postponed due to personnel changes in the Russian
government, writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo.
The delay in negotiations could cause increased resentment among Japanese,
who have been alarmed over reports that Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky, leader of
an extreme nationalist party, had threatened to bomb Japan if it pressed for
the return of the four islands, north of Hokkaido.
The Japanese government is, however, due to hold talks over bilateral
co-operation on environmental protection with South Korea and Russia this
month following the outcry caused by Russia's dumping of nuclear waste in
the Sea of Japan last year. This created tensions between Tokyo and Moscow,
which has since been calling for more foreign aid for its nuclear waste
management.
