<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Scalfaro prepares to call election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro last night looked set to dissolve Italy's
parliament and call general elections for late March following the
resignation of the eight-month-old Ciampi government.
Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the 73-year-old former governor of the bank of
Italy and the first non-elected premier this century, handed in his
resignation during a brief meeting with President Scalfaro early yesterday
afternoon.
The president did not formally accept the resignation. Officials said he was
anxious to consult with the leaders of the two houses of parliament and
other prominent politicians, first, to ensure Italy possessed a stable
caretaker government in the run-up to elections.
An announcement on the dissolution of parliament is expected at the weekend.
Elections must then be held within 60 days. Politicians said yesterday the
most likely dates would be March 20 or March 26.
Mr Ciampi's resignation followed an abortive attempt by a hard core of
Christian Democrats and their allies to prolong the life of the present
parliament, at least until June so as hold general elections alongside
European parliamentary elections.
The manoeuvre was backed by some Socialists, Social Democrats and Liberals
plus a group of mavericks among the Radicals and Republicans - in effect
those that have long dominated Italy's political life and risk oblivion in a
general election. Their aim was to delay elections as long as possible to
allow new parties to form, while at the same time exploiting their
parliamentary privileges to protect them from prosecution in the corruption
scandals.
In the classic manner of Italy's byzantine politics, the move to prolong
parliament took the form of a no-confidence motion tabled just before
Christmas. Thus the 170 signatories hoped to remove Mr Ciampi or ensure he
was forced to form a new government. This backfired when the motion began to
be debated on Wednesday and it became clear the motion lacked a majority in
the 630 seat house.
Yesterday, Mr Marco Panella, the Radical leader who tabled the motion,
withdrew it. The backers of the no- confidence motion then changed tactics
and proposed a confidence motion which has yet to be debated. Such a
confidence motion, however, threatens, if not carefully controlled, to
undermine the constitutional justification of President Scalfaro dissolving
parliament when the government enjoys the confidence of the legislature.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
