<DATE>940114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Three consortia seek to dial into Italian mobile network:
The race to win liberalised phone market licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
So popular has cellular telecommunications become in Italy that many fashion
houses are producing snappy designer pouches to hold the growing number of
phones in circulation.
The state airline, Alitalia, has started warning against the use of phones
on its flights. But this only provokes the same cravings as the ban on
smoking: as soon as the doors open dozens light up or start pushing buttons.
But cellular telephony is more than just a fad in Italy, whatever the
national propensity to follow fashion. As elsewhere in Europe, the ability
to make calls on the move has become a valuable business tool. The division
of responsibilities between the political capital in Rome and the business
centre in Milan means managers are often in transit.
In a country where ownership of a second, or even third, holiday home is not
just a luxury for the ultra-rich, access to a mobile phone can also
represent a saving compared with paying charges for a fixed line, which may
be used only occasionally.
The merits of the mobile phone are now so widely perceived that Italy has
become Europe's third-biggest market, with more than 1.1m subscribers. That
is still behind the UK - the biggest user of mobile telecommunications,
thanks to a relatively early start - but not far behind Germany, considering
the latter's bigger population.
For the companies jockeying to win the licence to run Italy's new
Europe-wide GSM standard network, the hope is that such sharp growth will
continue. Mr Tommaso Pompei, managing director of Pronto Italia, one of the
bidders, predicts subscribers will rise more than six-fold to about 8m by
the turn of the century.
Pronto Italia is one of three consortia putting the finishing touches to
their proposals before the pre-qualification deadline on Saturday. The
others are Unitel, composed of Fiat, Fininvest and Vodafone of the UK; and
Omnitel, comprising Olivetti, Swedish Telecom, BellAtlantic, Cellular
Communications and Lehman Brothers.
All three have been slightly taken aback by the speed with which Italy is
moving to liberalise its mobile telecommunications market after months of
false starts. Hitherto monopolised by the state-controlled Sip telephones
utility, the market is being opened up after pressure from the European
Commission in Brussels to meet European Union commitments on greater
competition.
After paying lip service in the past, matters have moved forward fast under
the government of Mr Carlo Azeglio Ciampi. The post and telecommunications
ministry has 15 days after the first deadline on Saturday to name companies
meeting its pre-qualification criteria. Although no timetable has been set
after that and matters could slip because of uncertainty surrounding new
elections, expected in March, a winner should be revealed by the end of
April.
The race has already produced some surprises. This week, Etra, one of the
bidding consortia, comprising subsidiaries of the big Eni energy and
chemicals group, Premafin, BellSouth and Millicom, said it was throwing in
its lot with Unitel, reducing the competition to a three-cornered fight.
Though that may have put Unitel in pole position, its two rivals are not
giving up. Mr Francesco Caio, Omnitel's chairman, says his consortium is the
only one to include a company - Olivetti - which sees telecommunications and
information technology services as core businesses. Having Swedish Telcom,
recently renamed Telia, on board adds a partner with a strong record from
the country with the highest per capita penetration of mobile phones, he
adds.
Perhaps reacting to lingering doubts about its precise composition, which
has yet to be revealed, Pronto Italia also stresses the experience of its
members. Mannesmann and Pacific Telesis, the two foreign partners, won the
mandate to operate Germany's GSM network, which has signed up 500,000
subscribers within 18 months of opening.
There is still some confusion about the other partners, however. Mr Pompei
says the remainder, comprising about 15 medium-sized Italian companies, will
only be revealed next week.
All three consortiums, which are expected easily to fulfil the
pre-qualification criteria, point to their financial muscle. Omnitel, in
which Lehman Brothers, the US investment bank, has 8 per cent, is raising
its capital to L200bn (Pounds 78m). Unitel is also planning a big rights
issue, opening the way for the entry of the Etra consortium members. Pronto
Italia, meanwhile, notes that its shareholders include some big banks.
Access to capital will be as important as having the right technology on
tap. Both Unitel and Omnitel have so far spent about L7bn just on
preliminary studies and market research. Pronto Italia, advised by SG
Warburg, the UK merchant bank, claims to have got through about L35bn.
Mr Nicolo Nefri, Unitel's chairman, confidently draws attention to the
combination of Fiat's industrial might with the marketing skills of Mr
Silvio Berlusconi's Fininvest group. The arrival of the Etra partners should
further enhance Unitel's image.
Olivetti, the main partner in Omnitel, has been pitching all out for the
business. With revenues from hardware in decline, it knows it must move into
services to maintain profitability, while distinctions between computers and
telecommunications are tending to blur.
The winner is unlikely to be known until after the elections. However, with
such powerful corporate forces at play, some cynics are already predicting
the mandate may eventually be awarded jointly to Unitel and Omnitel, which
would then join forces to run the new network together.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Pronto Italia.
    Unitel.
    Finanziaria d'Investimento.
    Vodafone Group.
    Omnitel.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ITZ  Italy, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4812 Radiotelephone Communications.
    P9631 Regulation, Administration of Utilities.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Patents &amp; Licences.
    TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
