<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / French employers in interest rate plea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Patronat, the French employers' federation, yesterday called for further
interest rate cuts, particularly for short-term loans, to help revive what
it described as the country's stagnant economy.
Mr Ernest-Antoine Selliere, the vice-chairman, said that gradual reduction
in French interest rates over recent months had been insufficient. 'Economic
activity has never revived without relatively low short-term interest
rates,' he told a press conference, calling on the newly-independent Bank of
France to show courage and move quickly to cut borrowing costs.
France's intervention rate, the floor for money market rates, currently
stands at 6.2 per cent. It has been gradually reduced since the summer's
currency crisis, but with inflation standing at an annual rate of just 2.1
per cent businesses still face relatively high real borrowing costs.
Mr Selliere gave a downbeat assessment of the state of the French economy.
'We are leaving recession, but the situation is fragile,' he said,
forecasting that gross domestic product would expand by between 0.5 per cent
and 1 per cent this year. The government is forecasting growth of 1.4 per
cent.
The Patronat vice-chairman also defended French industry against charges
that it has not done enough to help curb the rise in unemployment, which is
currently standing at more than 12 per cent of the workforce.
President Francois Mitterrand last week chastised employers for failing to
create jobs despite having received FFr80bn (Pounds 9bn) through the removal
of a delay in the reimbursement of value added tax payments, the transfer of
family allowance welfare contributions for low-paid workers from companies
to the state, and other measures. Mr Selliere also said he opposed a
proposal by Mr Edouard Balladur, the prime minister, that refunds of value
added tax should be conditional on job creation.
The proposal, made earlier this week, has drawn strong criticism from French
industrialists. Mr Jacques Calvet, chairman of the Peugeot-Citroen
automobile group rejected the idea as illogical. 'The state should pay back
companies the sums which they are owed. There should not be any conditions.'
</TEXT>
