<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Death of Norway's Mideast peacemaker: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MCDERMOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Johan Joergen Holst, Norway's foreign minister, has died in his sleep at
a recuperation centre outside Oslo after suffering two strokes. He was
central to the contacts between the Israeli government and the Palestine
Liberation Organisation which produced the peace handshake last September in
Washington between Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's prime minister, and Mr Yassir
Arafat, the PLO chairman.
Mr Holst was always one for overworking and the burden of too little sleep
and years of prodigious academic output on strategic issues took its toll.
Apart from his political career, he was head for many years of the Norwegian
Institute for International Affairs.
Born in 1937, Mr Holst was among a number of Norwegian politicians, part of
a tradition going back may years, to have an apparently disproportionate
influence on international affairs.
When he took over as foreign minister last April from Mr Thorvald
Stoltenberg, who left to become the United Nations peace envoy to former
Yugoslavia, the secret Middle East peace talks had already been under way
for several months. But they were still at a fragile early stage, lacking as
yet the participation of Israeli government officials.
Mr Holst later said he 'took over the baton' in a relay. It was a baton he
carried with enthusiasm and tenacity to the finishing line four months later
when he presided over the initialling of the declaration of principles at a
secret ceremony in Oslo in the early hours of August 20.
Mr Holst's role in the negotiations was probably most important at those
times when the talks were most in danger of collapse. In mid-July, a crisis
blew up at a session in Halvosbole, with the two leading PLO and Israeli
negotiators exchanging insults, and one threatening to pull out. Both sides
went home, leaving the negotiations apparently at an impasse.
After the Halvosbole row, Mr Holst spent long hours in Tunis with Mr Arafat
discussing the shape of the proposals so far drafted.
With other Norwegian mediators, they spread out maps of Israel and the
occupied territories, and pored over them while they debated key issues of
dispute. Mr Holst later said the meetings convinced him that Mr Arafat was
not only fully committed to achieving a settlement, but was personally in
charge of the PLO negotiating effort and fully briefed on all its aspects.
In letters, telephone calls and face-to-face meetings, Mr Holst conveyed
this conviction to Mr Shimon Peres, the Israeli foreign minister, and the
talks resumed. At the same time Mr Holst sought assurances from the Israeli
side that Mr Rabin was as committed as Mr Arafat.
In an interview later, Mr Holst said there was underlying the negotiations a
fundamental problem which he set about overcoming: the lack of essential
mutual confidence between the Israeli and PLO leaderships over their
respective commitment to the talks, and their ability to make a deal and
then to make it stick.
Mr Holst was also at the centre of the final negotiating session which
sealed the agreement.
It took place not in Oslo but in Stockholm, where Mr Holst was summoned at
short notice on August 17 by Mr Peres, who was on a visit.
An unfairness of his passing was the extent to which he looked after himself
physically. To ski with him was to watch with frustration his skilled
disappearance over the horizon. At other times, his passion for stamp
collecting more than once niggled his wife, Ms Marianne Heiberg - who was
central also to PLO-Israeli contacts. He was a fluent Russian speaker.
He had four children from a previous marriage and one from his present one.
His diplomatic skills, as a dedicated pro-Nato (he was tipped to succeed Mr
Manfred Worner as its chief) and Atlanticist advocate, outstripped his local
political instincts, although he was an assiduous worker for the Labour
party. Regarding him as aloof, the Norwegian press attacked him when he was
defence minister.
The strongest tributes came yesterday from Palestinians and Israelis alike.
Mr Rabin said: 'The state of Israel will remember Johan Joergen Holst as the
person who succeeded in bringing the distant together, in overcoming the
enmity of generations and in laying foundations for peace.'
Mr Arafat said: 'We lost with his early departure one of the sincerest
friends of our Palestinian people.' The PLO leader added: 'With this, he has
registered his name and his country's name in the pages of the world's
peace.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NOZ  Norway, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9199 General Government, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
