<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / Downing St tries to limit 'back to basics' damage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, DAVID OWEN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Downing Street launched an immediate damage limitation exercise last night
designed to keep the government's 'back to basics' initiative alive.
The move came as Tory MPs braced themselves for further damaging revelations
about the Westminster council affair.
Copies of the unpublished report circulating in the Commons were said to
contain further detailed allegations about how the gerrymandering was
conducted.
Gloomy Conservative MPs saw the report as a further instalment in the series
of disclosures which has rocked the government in the past two weeks.
Few blamed Mr Major for the latest revelations, but many said they would
have been less damaging under the leadership of a more resolute prime
minister.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's local government spokesman, said the report
disclosed political corruption on a scale unknown in modern Britain.
'It is the stuff of banana republics. It shows that the Tory party is
rotten, and amoral to the core. They have abandoned basic principles of
morality,' he said.
There was also concern about the position of Mr Barry Legg, Conservative MP
for Milton Keynes SW, who was chief whip to the Conservatives on Westminster
council in the period covered by the allegations.
Mr Legg, who could be surcharged if the Westminster district auditor decides
to pursue the issue in the courts, said he was innocent of any impropriety.
Labour also made clear that it would pursue allegations that Mr Peter
Brooke, the MP for Westminster South, knew about Westminster council's
housing policies when he was chairman of the Conservative party.
Several cabinet ministers are expected to make speeches on the initiative
today. They will include Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, and Mr Michael
Portillo, chief secretary to the treasury, who have differed strongly on the
moral content of the campaign.
Mr Major told the cabinet the campaign should not be derailed. 'The message
is sound. We must not let ourselves be diverted by isolated incidents. We
must keep our nerve,' he said.
'There is a moral dimension; it is not a moral crusade,' he was said to have
told ministers.
Mr Major won the support of the executive of the influential 1922 committee
of Conservative backbenchers at a long meeting last night, but MPs said
there had been tough exchanges.
Mr Major is understood to have been urged to act more decisively when
dealing with future ministerial indiscretions.
There was further gloom for the government in a Gallup poll for the Daily
Telegraph last night. The survey showed Labour on 46.5 per cent from 48.5
per cent in December.
Conservative support was at 25.5 per cent (27 per cent), with the Liberal
Democrats on 20.5 per cent (20 per cent).
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said last night that he had read the
British papers while abroad in recent days 'with growing disbelief'.
Mr Clarke said on BBC Question Time that he had 'come back to find that a
kind of hysteria is spreading, with allegations that are unsustainable
against any political party.'
</TEXT>
