<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 94 / District auditor's report: Main points
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Westminster city council had been guilty of 'gerrymandering' to give the
ruling party an unfair electoral advantage.
The council kept flats empty so that whole blocks could be sold to
owner-occupiers, preventing their use to house the homeless.
The council spent public funds to prepare papers for discussing the
promotion of the majority party's electoral advantage.
The sale of homes cost the council Pounds 21.25m, including Pounds 2m for
housing homeless families in temporary accommodation.
Ten councillors and officials - including Dame Shirley Porter, then council
leader - should be required to reimburse the council.
Six councillors - including Dame Shirley - should be disqualified from being
councillors.
